{"isSidechain":true,"agentId":"2d5be40f-7ed8-4fd","type":"assistant","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the plan carefully against the actual repo state.\n\nKey observations:\n\n1. VisualState contract: `accent_color: string`, `background_variant`, `card_variant`, `task_button_text`, `task_list_heading`, `profile_background`, `decorative_detail`, `level_up_text`, `empty_state_text`. No `accent_id`, no OD1/OD2 lilac/seed. The plan respects this. Good.\n\n2. The plan mentions `visualStateToCssVars(state, settings?)` returns `--accent, --bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg, --decor-detail, --task-button-text, --task-list-heading, --level-up-text, --empty-state-text, --reduced-motion`. But VisualState field is `profile_background` not `profile_bg`. Also there's no `decorative_detail` → `--decor-detail`. These are CSS var names, not contract field names — fine.\n\n3. The plan mentions ACCENT_CATALOG with raw hex in visual-state.ts. The project rules say \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback theme file\". visual-state.ts is described as \"fallback file, allowed\". This seems to be accepted per project rules. OK.\n\n4. Theme-color meta in nuxt.config.ts has hardcoded `#0e0f12`. The plan says it MAY touch nuxt.config.ts but doesn't mention updating theme-color to match new --bg #0D0F17. This is a minor inconsistency — the old theme-color would mismatch. But theme-color is not raw hex in CSS; it's a meta tag. Is this a real issue? The acceptance gate is \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\". nuxt.config.ts has `#0e0f12`. But the plan says it MAY touch nuxt.config.ts but doesn't list theme-color update. The existing committed `#0e0f12` in nuxt.config.ts would be pre-existing, out of write-scope similar to tailwind.config. Actually the plan lists nuxt.config.ts as MAY touch. So it's in write-scope. But the plan doesn't mention updating theme-color. This is a minor inconsistency but probably medium — the theme-color meta would mismatch the new --bg.\n\nActually wait — the raw-hex acceptance gate is scoped to NEW + allowed paths. The plan says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\". nuxt.config.ts already has `#0e0f12` committed. The plan doesn't introduce new raw hex there. But the plan changes --bg from #0e0f12 to #0D0F17. Leaving theme-color stale is a real visual defect (browser chrome color mismatch). Medium.\n\n5. The plan file 1 (tokens.scss ~115 LOC). Project rule: Files ≤150 LOC. 115 OK.\n\n6. scatter.ts ~95 LOC, visual-state.ts ~120 LOC — all under 150. OK.\n\n7. Logo.vue ~70 LOC, VisualBackground.vue ~90 LOC — under 150. OK.\n\n8. VisualBackground.vue: \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". The brand folder will have 6 SVGs. But the plan's file list (item 2) says \"copy 7 assets (chubzik-logo.png + 6 svg)\". But the source assets listed are: logo.png, magic-spark.svg, magic-curl.svg, magic-orbit.svg, magic-thread.svg, magic-wisp.svg, tiny-spark.svg = 1 PNG + 6 SVG. But the plan says \"chubzik-logo.png\" while the source is \"logo.png\". The prior feedback says logo.png. The plan renames to chubzik-logo.png. Is that a problem? The plan says \"copy 7 assets (chubzik-logo.png + 6 svg)\" — so it renames logo.png → chubzik-logo.png. That's fine as long as consistent. assets.ts LOGO_FILE='chubzik-logo.png'. OK.\n\nWait, but there are 7 SVGs listed in source? Let me recount: magic-spark, magic-curl, magic-orbit, magic-thread, magic-wisp, tiny-spark = 6 SVGs. Plus logo.png = 7 total. Plan says \"6 svg\". OK consistent.\n\n9. The plan mentions `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`. But VisualState.accent_color is a string from backend. The fallback in visual-state.ts ACCENT_CATALOG. The default --accent in tokens.scss is #7dd3fc. Is #7dd3fc lilac? No, it's light blue (sky-300). The project rule says \"no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed\". OK.\n\nBut wait — the OLD main.scss had `--accent: #7c5cff` which IS lilac/purple. The plan changes it to #7dd3fc (light blue). This is the runtime default. Good — non-lilac.\n\n10. The plan's tokens.scss lists `--magic #B9A7FF` which IS lilac/purple (#B9A7FF = light purple/lilac). But this is a fixed semantic token for \"magic\" decoration, not the accent. The project rule says \"no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed\" — referring to VisualState fields, not decoration colors. #B9A7FF as --magic is a decorative token, fixed. Hmm, is this a violation? The rule \"VisualState fields fixed (no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed)\" — this is about not adding lilac/seed to VisualState type. --magic being lilac is a design choice, not a VisualState field. Probably acceptable. Not raising.\n\n11. scatter.ts LAYOUT_TABLE: Record<detail, ScatterItem[]> with ~6 each. detail = decorative_detail: \"soft-sparks\" | \"thin-rings\" | \"small-dots\". But VisualBackground imports SVG assets. The scatterLayout returns asset names. The SVGs available are magic-spark, magic-curl, magic-orbit, magic-thread, magic-wisp, tiny-spark. For \"thin-rings\" detail, the asset would be... magic-orbit (ring-like). For \"small-dots\", tiny-spark. For \"soft-sparks\", magic-spark/magic-wisp. The plan says ScatterItem has `asset` field referencing which SVG. This needs to map to actual SVG filenames. The plan doesn't detail the exact mapping but that's implementation detail, acceptable for a plan.\n\n12. visual-state.ts self-check: `npx tsx shared/visual/visual-state.ts`. The repo uses bun (bun run typecheck). Using npx tsx should work if tsx is installed. Let me check. Actually the acceptance says \"tsx self-checks pass\". The plan uses `npx tsx`. Is tsx available? Let me check package.json / node_modules. Actually this is a plan — the implementation will need tsx. Let me verify.\n\nActually, the plan says run `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`. npx will fetch tsx if not installed. That's fine for self-check. OK.\n\n13. The plan's main.scss wiring: \"replace `:root{...}` block with `@use './tokens.scss';`\". But `@use` in SCSS loads tokens into a namespace by default. `@use './tokens.scss';` without `as` would make tokens available as `tokens.scss` namespace? Actually `@use './tokens.scss'` without `as` uses the filename as namespace. But the tokens defined in tokens.scss as CSS custom properties (`:root { --bg: ... }`) — these are plain CSS, not SCSS variables. `@use` would include the CSS output. Actually `@use` includes the CSS output of the module once. So `:root{...}` in tokens.scss would be emitted once when `@use`'d. But `@use` is namespaced for SCSS members (variables, mixins, functions), not for plain CSS. Plain CSS rules in a `@use`'d module ARE emitted. So `@use './tokens.scss'` would emit the `:root{}` block. But the body/focus/.display etc. in main.scss use `var(--bg)` which are runtime CSS custom properties — they resolve regardless of SCSS namespace. So `@use './tokens.scss'` works for emitting the `:root` tokens. OK. Though `@forward` or just plain `@use` — fine.\n\nActually there's a subtlety: `@use` without `as` — the namespace defaults to the file basename. But for plain CSS rules, there's no namespace needed; they're emitted. This works. OK.\n\n14. app.vue: \"add <VisualBackground/> as first child inside a relative wrapper; keep NuxtLayout/NuxtPage.\" The current app.vue is:\n```\n<template>\n  <NuxtLayout>\n    <NuxtPage />\n  </NuxtLayout>\n</template>\n```\nAdding VisualBackground inside a relative wrapper — where? \"inside a relative wrapper\" — probably wrapping NuxtLayout. But the plan says \"keep NuxtLayout/NuxtPage\". So:\n```\n<template>\n  <div class=\"relative\">\n    <VisualBackground />\n    <NuxtLayout>\n      <NuxtPage />\n    </NuxtLayout>\n  </div>\n</template>\n```\nThis is reasonable. OK.\n\n15. Acceptance: \"rg Math.random apps shared none\" — the plan says NOT doing Math.random. Good. But scatter.ts has fixed LAYOUT_TABLE (no randomness). Good. But the project rule says \"NO Math.random for visual\" — the plan complies