e, settings?)`. OK, settings optional. Good.\n\n23. Where are the CSS vars applied? The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns a Record<string,string>. But who applies them to :root? The plan doesn't explicitly say. VisualBackground.vue reads --reduced-motion via getComputedStyle — implying the vars are set somewhere on :root. But the plan doesn't mention a plugin or app.vue setting these vars. This is a GAP. The plan creates visualStateToCssVars but doesn't wire it to actually set the CSS variables on the document. VisualBackground reads --reduced-motion but nothing sets it.\n\nWait — is this packet P09-1 (visual foundation). The actual visual state wiring from backend might be a later packet. But the plan defines visualStateToCssVars and FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE. If nothing applies these vars, then --bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg, --decor-detail, --task-button-text, etc. are never set. VisualBackground only uses --reduced-motion and --brand-decoration-* tokens (from tokens.scss). So the scatter rendering would still work via tokens.scss defaults.\n\nBut --reduced-motion: tokens.scss doesn't define --reduced-motion. visualStateToCssVars returns it. But nothing applies it. So getComputedStyle for --reduced-motion would return empty. VisualBackground's reduced ref would be false (fallback). Is this a defect? The plan says VisualBackground \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var... with getComputedStyle in onMounted → set local reduced ref\". If the var isn't set, it falls back to prefers-reduced-motion media query. So it degrades gracefully. Not critical.\n\nBut the broader issue: visualStateToCssVars produces vars that nothing consumes in this packet. Is that scope-appropriate? The plan is \"visual foundation\" — providing the function for later packets to use. That's reasonable for a foundation packet. The acceptance doesn't require the vars to be applied. OK, not raising.\n\n24. Actually, a real concern: the plan says tokens.scss defines `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`. But `--accent` as a default in tokens.scss, and visualStateToCssVars ALSO returns `--accent`. If both set --accent, the runtime one (applied later) overrides the tokens.scss default. Fine. But in THIS packet, nothing applies visualStateToCssVars, so --accent stays #7dd3fc from tokens.scss. OK.\n\n25. LOC concern: visual-state.ts ~120 LOC with ACCENT_CATALOG (raw hex catalog, could be many entries), FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE, visualStateToCssVars function, validation, self-check assert block. 120 LOC seems tight but plausible. OK.\n\n26. The plan's file 6 (index.ts ~5 LOC) re-exports 3 modules: assets, scatter, visual-state. But shared/visual/ also needs to be importable from apps/mobile/visual.ts via `export * from \"../../shared/visual\"`. That re-exports index.ts. OK.\n\nBut wait — does `shared/visual/index.ts` exist currently? No (shared/visual/ doesn't exist yet). The plan creates it. OK.\n\n27. The acceptance says `cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck` passes. The typecheck is `nuxt typecheck` (vue-tsc). For this to include shared/visual/*.ts, the tsconfig must reference them. The apps/mobile/tsconfig.json extends .nuxt/tsconfig.json. Does .nuxt/tsconfig.json include shared/? Probably not by default. The shared/ files would need to be imported via the `../../shared/visual` path from apps/mobile/visual.ts. vue-tsc would follow imports. But would it type-check shared/visual files? It would if imported. apps/mobile/visual.ts re-exports, but is apps/mobile/visual.ts imported by anything? If nothing imports it, typecheck might not cover it.\n\nHmm, actually the plan creates apps/mobile/visual.ts = `export * from \"../../shared/visual\"`. If nothing in the app imports from `~/visual` or `../../visual`, then this file is unused and typecheck might not check shared/visual. But the self-checks (npx tsx) cover shared/visual directly. The acceptance says \"tsx self-checks pass; typecheck passes\". So both. OK.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue