his packet). So the gate passes. But if the plan SHOULD update theme-color to #0D0F17, that introduces raw hex in nuxt.config.ts, violating the gate. Conflict!\n\nSo either:\n(a) Leave theme-color stale (#0e0f12 ≠ #0D0F17) — visual mismatch, medium issue.\n(b) Update theme-color to #0D0F17 — introduces raw hex in nuxt.config.ts, violating \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts\".\n\nThe plan chose (a) implicitly. The cleaner solution: reference theme-color via a build-time substitution or accept the mismatch. Actually, theme-color in nuxt.config.ts is a static string; it can't use CSS vars. So it must be raw hex. The acceptance gate would need to allow nuxt.config.ts theme-color as an exception, OR keep it stale.\n\nThis is a genuine plan gap: the plan doesn't address the theme-color staleness/mismatch. Medium.\n\n31. Let me also reconsider: the plan says tokens.scss has `--bg #0D0F17` but the OLD main.scss had `--bg #0e0f12`. The plan changes the canonical bg. Is this intended? Yes, the plan defines new canonical tokens. Fine.\n\n32. Another concern: the plan's VisualBackground imports \"each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". In Nuxt/Vite, importing SVG as URL — by default Vite returns the URL for SVG imports? Actually Vite handles `import url from './x.svg'` → returns the resolved URL string. Yes, Vite supports this. OK.\n\nBut there are 6 SVGs and 3 detail variants. The LAYOUT_TABLE maps detail → ScatterItem[] where each ScatterItem.asset is a name. VisualBackground needs to map asset name → imported URL. The plan says \"import each svg url\". So VisualBackground imports all 6 SVGs and maps by name. OK.\n\n33. The plan's scatter.ts ScatterItem = {x, y, rotation, scale, asset}. The LAYOUT_TABLE is `Record<detail, ScatterItem[]>` — but detail type is \"soft-sparks\" | \"thin-rings\" | \"small-dots\". scatter.ts needs to import this type from contracts. The plan says \"Pure data, no DOM\". It imports the type from shared/contracts/visual-settings. OK.\n\nBut wait — is shared/visual allowed to import from shared/contracts? The allowed write paths are shared/visual/**. shared/contracts is existing (not being written). Importing from it is fine (read-only). OK.\n\n34. The plan says scatter.ts self-check \"via assert + if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))\". This uses `fileURLToPath` from `node:url` and `import.meta.url`. For a .ts file run with tsx, this works. OK.\n\n35. Let me reconsider the LOC for tokens.scss. The plan lists many tokens. Let me count lines if each token is one line + comments:\n- Canonical: ~14 lines\n- Semantic aliases: ~10\n- Legacy: ~8\n- Variant tints: ~9\n- Non-color: ~12\nTotal variable lines: ~53. With comments and grouping, ~115 LOC. OK under 150.\n\n36. One more: the plan says \"ponytail: comment on legacy aliases.\" This is a note to add a comment explaining legacy aliases. Fine.\n\n37. Does the plan address all TASK requirements? The task is \"P09-1 visual foundation\". The plan covers tokens, assets, scatter, visual-state, Logo, VisualBackground, wiring. Seems complete for a foundation packet.\n\n38. Let me reconsider whether there are any critical issues. The theme-color mismatch is medium. \n\n39. Actually, let me reconsider the `@use './tokens.scss'` approach. In SCSS, `@use` with a file that only contains plain CSS (no SCSS variables/mixins) — it emits the CSS. But there's a gotcha: `@use` must be at the top of the file, before any other rules. The plan says \"replace :root{...} block with @use './tokens.scss'\". The :root block is at the top of main.scss (lines 1-25). After it comes `* { box-sizing }` etc. So `@use` would be at the top. Good. But the plan also says \"Keep body/focus/.display/.text-grad/.tap/a.\" These come after. `@use` at top, then body etc. Valid SCSS. OK.\n\nBut actually — `@use` emits the CSS from tokens.scss. But does it emit `:root {}` from tokens.scss into the output? Yes. So the final CSS has `:root { --bg: ...; ... }` from tokens.scss, then body etc. from main.scss. Good.\n\n40. Hmm, one concern: the plan says tokens.scss contains `--accent default #7dd3fc` and also visual-state.ts has ACCENT_CATALOG with raw hex. The acceptance says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\". But assets = PNG/SVG binary, not hex. So \"assets\" here means the brand image files. OK. The gate is about source code hex. Fine.\n\n41. Let me reconsider if there's a high-severity issue. The plan seems fairly thorough. \n\nOne potential high issue: the plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg`. But tokens.scss defines variant tints: `--bg-dark-ember/--bg-deep-forest/--bg-midnight`, `--card-graphite/--card-pine/--card-plum`, `--profile-quiet-grid/--profile-night-lines/--profile-calm-shapes`. So visualStateToCssVars should return `--bg-variant: var(--bg-dark-ember)` etc. (mapping state → token). The plan says it returns `--bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg` as CSS vars. The VALUES would be `var(--bg-dark-ember)` (semantic alias to token). This is the right pattern. OK.\n\nBut the plan doesn't explicitly say the values are var() references. It says \"visualStateToCssVars(state, settings?) → Record<string,string>\". The implementation would map state.background_variant=\"dark-ember\" → `--bg-variant: var(--bg-dark-ember)`. This is implementation detail. OK for plan.\n\n42. Let me reconsider the `--accent` default. tokens.scss sets `--accent: #7dd3fc`. visualStateToCssVars returns `--accent: <hex from catalog>`. But in THIS packet, nothing applies visualStateToCssVars. So --accent = #7dd3fc. But the old main.scss had --accent: #7c5cff (lilac). The plan changes the default accent to non-lilac. Good per project rules.\n\nBut wait — P10 pages (login.vue, FormField.vue, tailwind) use --accent. If the default changes from lilac to light-blue, P10 pages would change appearance. Is that intended? The plan says \"tokens.scss keeps --accent-weak legacy token (used by P10)\". But --accent itself changes. The prior feedback says raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope. But tailwind.config.ts might reference --accent via CSS var, or have its own hex. If tailwind has its own hex accent, the visual change might be limited. If tailwind uses var(--accent), the P10 pages would shift from lilac to light-blue.\n\nIs this a regression? The plan is P09-1 visual foundation. Changing the default --accent is part of the rebrand. But it could break P10 visual consistency. However, P10 is out of scope and the plan explicitly says \"not regressed\". Changing --accent default IS a change that affects P10. Is this \"regression\"? \n\nHmm. The prior feedback says \"pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope (P10) and left untouched (not regressed, not introduced by this packet)\". So the raw hex in tailwind is untouched. But if tailwind.config.ts defines accent as `#7c5cff` (raw) rather than `var(--accent)`, then changing tokens.scss --accent doesn't affect tailwind. Let me check.\n\nLet me look at tailwind.config.ts.\n\nActually I should verify this to determine if changing --accent default regresses P10.\n\nLet me check.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-a20e6cc71b199e9b","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /usr/projects/Диплом && cat apps/mobile/tailwind.config.ts 2>/dev/null | head -60; echo \"===\"; rg -n \"var\\(--accent|--accent\" apps/mobile/app/components/ui/AppButton.vue 2>/dev/null | head; echo \"===\"; cat apps/mobile/api.ts 2>/dev/null"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-a6a454a2606ac563","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /usr/projects/Диплом && rg -n \"rgba?\\(|#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,6}\" apps/mobile/tailwind.config.ts 2>/dev/null | head -20; echo \"===\"; rg -ln \"tsx\" apps/mobile/node_modules/.bin/ 2>/dev/null | head; which tsx 2>/dev/null; cd /usr/projects/Диплом && ls node_modules/.bin/tsx 2>/dev/null; echo \"===\