{"isSidechain":true,"agentId":"2d5be40f-7ed8-4fd","type":"assistant","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me analyze the plan thoroughly. Let me check key issues:\n\n1. **Theme-color in nuxt.config.ts is `#0e0f12`** — but the plan changes `--bg` to `#0D0F17` (new canonical). The plan says nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch paths. But the plan doesn't mention updating theme-color to match the new `--bg #0D0F17`. This is a real inconsistency — the theme-color meta tag would stay at the old hex while the actual background token changes. This is at least medium.\n\n2. **Tailwind config still references old hex colors** (`#0e0f12`, `#7c5cff`, etc.) — the plan does NOT touch tailwind.config.ts (not in allowed write paths except... let me check: ALLOWED WRITE PATHS doesn't include tailwind.config.ts). The plan says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" as acceptance. But tailwind.config.ts already has raw hex committed. The prior feedback says \"pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope (P10) and left untouched (not regressed, not introduced by this packet).\" So the acceptance gate is \"scoped to NEW + allowed paths only.\" OK, so this is acknowledged — tailwind.config.ts raw hex is pre-existing and out of scope. Not an issue.\n\n3. **`npx tsx` availability**: The plan says \"Run: `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`\" and `npx tsx shared/visual/visual-state.ts`. But `tsx` is not in package.json dependencies, and `npx tsx` would download it on the fly. This could work but is fragile. Let me check if tsx is installed anywhere... It's not. `npx tsx` would fetch it. This is a real concern — the self-check acceptance commands depend on a package that isn't a declared dependency. But `npx` will download it. This is at least medium — the verification command may not work reliably / introduces an undeclared dependency. Actually, let me think about this more. The plan uses `np