(5). tiny-spark isn't a \"magic\" SVG. Let me check if VisualBackground uses tiny-spark too. The plan says FALLBACK_DECOR='soft-sparks' and VisualBackground renders scatterLayout items. The LAYOUT_TABLE has ~6 items each per detail. With 3 detail options (soft-sparks, thin-rings, small-dots) × ~6 items = ~18 scatter positions. But there are only 6 SVG assets to choose from. This should be fine — the same SVG can appear at multiple positions.\n\nActually, the concern is: does MAGIC_SVG_FILES include tiny-spark? The plan says `MAGIC_SVG_FILES=['magic-spark',...6]` — the `...6` is ambiguous. It could mean \"and 5 more = 6 total\" or \"6 magic ones\". But there are only 5 magic-* SVGs. If MAGIC_SVG_FILES has 6 entries, it must include tiny-spark. This is a minor ambiguity but the naming is misleading. Not a medium+ issue though.\n\n6. **VisualBackground SVG imports**: The plan says VisualBackground \"renders scatterLayout(detail) items as positioned <span> mask SVGs (import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg)\". This means VisualBackground will import each of the 6 SVG files individually. That's fine. But the scatter.ts returns `asset` field per ScatterItem — this should be the SVG name (e.g., \"magic-spark\"). VisualBackground then needs to map asset name → imported URL. The plan mentions \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\" — so it statically imports them. This works.\n\n7. **LOC limits**: PROJECT_RULES says \"Files ≤150 LOC\". Let me check:\n   - tokens.scss ~115 LOC ✓\n   - visual-state.ts ~120 LOC ✓ (close to limit)\n   - scatter.ts ~95 LOC ✓\n   - VisualBackground.vue ~90 LOC ✓\n   - Logo.vue ~70 LOC ✓\n   - assets.ts ~30 LOC ✓\n   - index.ts ~5 LOC ✓\n   All within 150. OK.\n\n8. **Raw hex in visual-state.ts**: The plan says \"ACCENT_CATALOG const (raw hex — fallback file, allowed)\". PROJECT_RULES says \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback theme file\". So visual-state.ts acts as the \"fallback theme file\". The prior feedback confirms this is allowed. OK.\n\n9. **--accent default #7dd3fc**: The plan says `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`. The old --accent was `#7c5cff` (lilac/purple). The new default is `#7dd3fc` (light blue/cyan). But the tailwind.config.ts still has `accent: \"#7c5cff\"`. The plan doesn't touch tailwind.config.ts. So there's a divergence: CSS --accent will be #7dd3fc but Tailwind's `accent` color utility will be #7c5cff. If any component uses Tailwind `accent-*` classes... let me check. Earlier grep showed no Tailwind color classes being used (only `text-grad`, `display`, `tap` custom classes). So this divergence is latent but not currently broken. Not a medium+ issue for this packet.\n\n10. **nuxt.config.ts theme-color**: The plan says nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch paths, but the plan doesn't mention updating `theme-color` from `#0e0f12` to the new `--bg #0D0F17`. This is a real issue — the browser chrome color will mismatch the actual background. The plan item #11 says \"app.vue — add <VisualBackground/>\" but doesn't mention updating nuxt.config.ts theme-color. And the canonical --bg is changing from #0e0f12 to #0D0F17. This is at least medium — the theme-color meta should match the new --bg.\n\nActually wait — does the plan explicitly change --bg to #0D0F17? Yes: \"Canonical color tokens (--bg #0D0F17, ...)\". The current main.scss has `--bg: #0e0f12`. The new tokens.scss will have `--bg: #0D0F17`. So the theme-color `#0e0f12` in nuxt.config.ts becomes stale. This is a real defect — the plan should update it since nuxt.config.ts is in the MAY touch list.\n\n11. **main.scss `@use` vs `:root`**: The plan says \"replace `:root{...}` block with `@use './tokens.scss';`\". SCSS `@use` loads a module — but `@use` doesn't inject CSS by default; it makes members available as namespace. To actually emit the `:root` block from tokens.scss into the output, you'd use `@use './tokens.scss';` and tokens.scss would have `:root { ... }` at the top level. With `@use`, the CSS in the used file IS emitted. Actually, `@use` does include the CSS rules from the used file. Yes, `@use` will emit the `:root` block from tokens.scss. So this works. Good.\n\nBut wait — `@use` with plain CSS custom properties in `:root` — that's fine. The custom properties are just CSS, not SCSS variables, so `@use` will emit them. OK.\n\n12. **VisualState field names**: The contract has `accent_color: string` (not `accent`). The plan's visualStateToCssVars returns `--accent`. The mapping is `accent_color` → `--accent`. Fine, the plan is mapping the contract field to a CSS var. The contract field name is `accent_color`, and the plan's VisualState fields are \"fixed (no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed)\" — consistent with the contract. OK.\n\nBut wait — the plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--accent`, `--bg-variant`, `--card-variant`, `--profile-bg`, `--decor-detail`, `--task-button-text`, `--task-list-heading`, `--level-up-text`, `--empty-state-text`, `--reduced-motion`. These CSS vars map to VisualState fields:\n- accent_color → --accent ✓\n- background_variant → --bg-variant ✓ (but tokens.scss defines --bg-dark-ember etc. — so --bg-variant would be set to `var(--bg-dark-ember)` etc.?)\n- card_variant → --card-variant ✓\n- profile_background → --profile-bg ✓\n- decorative_detail → --decor-detail ✓\n- task_button_text → --task-button-text ✓\n- task_list_heading → --task-list-heading ✓\n- level_up_text → --level-up-text ✓\n- empty_state_text → --empty-state-text ✓\n- reduced_motion (from Settings, not VisualState) → --reduced-motion ✓\n\nThe function signature is `visualStateToCssVars(state, settings?)` — settings is optional, for reduced_motion and disable_visual_randomness. This is reasonable.\n\n13. **Self-check assertion approach**: The plan uses `assert` + `if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))`. This is a valid Node self-check pattern. With tsx, `process.argv[1]` would be the file path. `import.meta.url` would be the file URL. `fileURLToPath` converts it to a path. This comparison works. OK.\n\nBut `assert` in Node.js — the global `assert` from `node:assert`? The plan says \"Self-check via assert\" — it should `import assert from 'node:assert'` or use `import { strict as assert } from 'node:assert'`. If the plan just uses bare `assert` without importing, it would fail. But the plan says \"Self-check via assert + ...\" — the implementation would import it. This is a plan, not implementation, so this level of detail is acceptable. Not an issue.\n\n14. **shared/visual/ is a new directory** — creating it is fine since `shared/visual/**` is in allowed write paths.\n\n15. **apps/mobile/visual.ts** — re-export from `../../shared/visual`. The path from `apps/mobile/visual.ts` to `shared/visual/` would be `../../shared/visual/`. Let me verify: `apps/mobile/visual.ts` → `../` = `apps/` → `../` = root → `shared/visual/`. Yes, `../../shared/visual` is correct. OK. But wait — does apps/mobile/visual.ts exist already? Earlier `cat apps/mobile/visual.ts` returned empty (no output, exit code 2 for `ls apps/mobile/app/assets/brand/`). Let me check — the prior feedback says \"apps/mobile/visual.ts = `export * from \"../../shared/visual\"` (mirror api.ts).\" and api.ts is `export * from \"../../shared/api\"`. So visual.ts mirrors this pattern. OK.\n\n16. **Tokens.scss changing `--bg` value breaks tailwind.config.ts divergence**: tailwind.config.ts has `bg: \"#0e0f12\"` but tokens.scss will have `--bg: #0D0F17`. If Tailwind's `bg-bg` utility is used... but grep showed no Tailwind color utilities are used. So latent, not active. Not raising.\n\n17. **Color migration from old to new palette**: The plan changes several core colors:\n- --bg: #0e0f12 → #0D0F17\n- --surface: #171a20 → #181B25\n- --surface-2: #1f232b → #222635\n- --text: #e7e9ee → #F4F0E8\n- --muted: #9aa0ab → #9EA7B8\n- --accent: #7c5cff → #7dd3fc\n- New tokens: --stroke, --magic, --mana, --xp, --blue, --danger\n\nThe components in P10 scope (login.vue, FormField.vue, AppButton.vue, BottomNav.vue, AppHeader.vue) reference `var(--accent-grad)`, `var(--accent)`, `var(--accent-weak)`, `var(--ring)`, `var(--muted)`, etc. The plan keeps these legacy aliases in tokens.scss via var(). So existing components continue to work. Good.\n\nBut the legacy `--accent-grad` was `linear-gradient(135deg, #7c5cff 0%, #4dd4ff 100%)`. The new plan says `--accent-grad` is a \"Legacy P10-compat utility token via var()\". But the gradient used the OLD accent colors (#7c5cff, #4dd4ff). The new --accent is #7dd3fc. If --accent-grad still uses the old lilac colors, it would be visually inconsistent with the new --accent. But the plan says these are \"legacy P10-compat\" — meaning they're kept for backward compatibility. The new --accent is non-lilac, but --accent-grad might still be lilac. Is this a problem?\n\nThe PROJECT_RULES say \"no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed\" for VisualState fields. But --accent-grad being lilac for P10 compat is a separate concern. The prior feedback explicitly allows keeping --accent-weak. But does it allow --accent-grad to remain lilac?\n\nActually, the plan says `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`. The runtime --accent comes from visualStateToCssVars. But --accent-grad is a static token. If --accent-grad references the old lilac colors, components using --accent-grad (AppButton, AppHeader, text-grad) would show lilac gradients while --accent is light blue. This is a visual inconsistency but it's P10 compat — these components are out of scope for P09. The plan's intent is to provide the tokens so P10 can later migrate. So this is acceptable for now.\n\nActually wait — the plan says `--accent-grad` via var(). Let me re-read: \"Legacy P10-compat utility tokens via var(): --accent-grad, --accent-2, ...\". The \"via var()\" means these are defined using var() references to canonical tokens, not raw hex. So --accent-grad would be something like `linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent) 0%, var(--accent-2) 100%)`. If --accent-2 is the old #4dd4ff... but the plan says --accent-2 is a legacy alias via var(). What does --accent-2 reference? The plan doesn't specify. This is a bit vague but it's a plan, not implementation. The key point is: these legacy aliases use var() not raw hex. OK.\n\n18. **AppButton.vue has hardcoded `rgba(124, 92, 255, ...)` and `#fff`** — these are out of write scope (P10). Prior feedback acknowledges this. Not raising.\n\n19. **nuxt.config.ts theme-color** — this is the strongest issue. The plan changes --bg to #0D0F17 but leaves theme-color at #0e0f12. nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch paths. This is a real medium issue.\n\n20. **Verification commands**: The plan says acceptance includes `tsx self-checks pass; cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck passes; rg Math.random apps shared none; rg fonts.googleapis|gstatic none; raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets`. These are concrete commands. The typecheck command is `bun run typecheck` which maps to `nuxt typecheck`. Good.\n\nBut `npx tsx` isn't declared as a dependency. If there's no network access during verification, this fails. Actually the prior feedback in round 1 didn't flag this, and it's a common pattern. Let me check if the verification section says specifically \"npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts\" — yes. This is a runnable command. OK, not raising — it's a valid verification approach.\n\n21. **Does the plan address the TASK?** The task is \"visual foundation\" — establishing the visual token system, brand assets, scatter layout, visual state mapping, Logo and VisualBackground components. The plan covers all of this. OK.\n\n22. **Missing file in Files-to-touch**: The plan lists all files. Let me check if app.vue is listed — yes, item #11. main.scss — item #10. nuxt.config.ts — it's in MAY touch but not explicitly listed as a file to modify. If the theme-color issue is raised, this would be the fix: add nuxt.config.ts to the modification list and update theme-color.\n\n23. **The raw-hex acceptance gate**: \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\". But the plan also has `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`. So tokens.scss has raw hex (allowed). visual-state.ts has ACCENT_CATALOG with raw hex (allowed as fallback theme file). The acceptance gate says raw hex only in these + assets. But AppButton.vue, BottomNav.vue, AppHeader.vue have raw hex (`#fff`, `rgba(124,92,255,...)`). The prior feedback says these are out of write-scope and \"not regressed, not introduced by this packet.\" The acceptance gate is \"scoped to NEW + allowed paths only.\" So the rg check would need to be scoped. The plan says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — but this would FAIL if rg is run across all files, because AppButton.vue etc. have raw hex. The plan's acceptance statement is misleading/incorrect.\n\nActually, the prior feedback explicitly says: \"raw-hex acceptance gate scoped to NEW + allowed paths only; pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope (P10) and left untouched.\" So the acceptance gate should be scoped. But the plan's acceptance section says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" without specifying the scope. If someone runs `rg '#[0-9a-f]{6}' apps/ shared/` it would find hex in AppButton.vue, BottomNav.vue, etc. and fail. The plan should specify the scoped rg command. This is a medium issue — the acceptance command as stated would fail.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"Acceptance: tsx self-checks pass; `cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck` passes; rg Math.random apps shared none; rg fonts.googleapis|gstatic none; raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\"\n\nThe \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" is stated as a claim, not a specific rg command. The prior feedback says it's scoped to NEW + allowed paths. But the plan doesn't specify the scoped command. If the implementation follows the plan literally, the verification would need a scoped rg. The plan should specify the exact rg command with path scoping. This is a medium issue — the verification is ambiguous and would fail if run unscoped.\n\nActually, `rgba(124, 92, 255, ...)` — is rgba considered \"raw hex\"? The prior feedback says \"raw hex\" specifically. rgba() with numeric values isn't hex. So `rg '#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,6}'` would catch hex but not rgba. AppButton.vue has `#fff` (hex) — that would be caught. And `rgba(124,92,255,...)` wouldn't be caught by a hex regex.\n\nSo the raw hex in AppButton.vue (`#fff`, `#fff`) would be caught by `rg '#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,6}\\b'`. tailwind.config.ts has hex. nuxt.config.ts has `#0e0f12`. These are pre-existing. The acceptance claim \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" is FALSE if checked across the whole repo. The plan needs to specify the scoped command. Medium issue.\n\n24. Let me also check: the plan says `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`. The old main.scss has `--accent-weak: #2a2347;`. The plan keeps this as raw hex in tokens.scss. tokens.scss is an allowed raw-hex file. OK.\n\n25. **VisualBackground `getComputedStyle` in onMounted**: The plan says \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via v-bind-less approach: use `@media (prefers-reduced-motion)` + check --reduced-motion var with getComputedStyle in onMounted → set local `reduced` ref.\" This is reasonable but getComputedStyle reads CSS custom properties. `getComputedStyle(document.documentElement).getPropertyValue('--reduced-motion')` — this would work if --reduced-motion is set on :root by visualStateToCssVars. But visualStateToCssVars returns a Record<string,string> — where are these applied to the DOM? The plan doesn't mention where visualStateToCssVars output is applied. Presumably on a root element's style. But this is P11/P12 wiring, not P09. In P09, VisualBackground just needs to read --reduced-motion if it exists. The getComputedStyle approach handles the case where it's not set (returns empty string). OK, not an issue for the plan.\n\n26. **Logo.vue mask approach**: `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` — using v-bind in <style>. PROJECT_RULES say \"Vue v-bind() in styles OK.\" The logoUrl is imported via `import logoUrl from '~/assets/brand/chubzik-logo.png'`. In Nuxt/Vite, PNG imports return a URL string. v-bind(logoUrl) in <style scoped> would resolve to that URL. `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` — this produces `mask: url(/path/to/chubzik-logo.png)`. This works. OK.\n\nBut wait — `mask: url(...)` without `-webkit-` prefix. For Safari/iOS (Capacitor), `-webkit-mask` is needed. The plan doesn't mention `-webkit-mask`. On iOS WebKit, `mask` without `-webkit-` prefix may not work. This is a real issue for a mobile app. Medium.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Modern Safari (iOS 15+) supports unprefixed `mask`. But Capacitor uses WKWebView which is Safari-based. For broad compatibility, `-webkit-mask` is still recommended. But this is borderline — modern WebKit supports `mask`. I'll consider this a medium issue since it's a mobile app targeting WebKit and the plan doesn't address the prefix.\n\nHmm, actually let me not raise this — modern Safari does support `mask` unprefixed. It's not a clear defect. I'll skip it.\n\n27. Let me check the main concern: **nuxt.config.ts theme-color mismatch**. This is the clearest issue. The plan changes --bg to #0D0F17 but doesn't update the `theme-color` meta tag in nuxt.config.ts (which is in MAY touch paths). Medium.\n\n28. **Acceptance raw-hex claim is unscoped**. The plan says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" but pre-existing hex exists in tailwind.config.ts, nuxt.config.ts, AppButton.vue, etc. The acceptance claim is misleading without a scoped rg command. The prior feedback says it's scoped, but the plan's acceptance section doesn't specify the scoping. Medium — the verification as stated would fail.\n\nLet me finalize. I have two solid medium issues:\n\n1. nuxt.config.ts theme-color `#0e0f12` will mismatch new `--bg #0D0F17` — plan doesn't update it despite being in MAY touch paths.\n2. Acceptance raw-hex claim \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" is unscoped and would fail against pre-existing committed hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue/nuxt.config.ts.\n\nThese are both medium. Let me write the feedback.\n\nActually, let me reconsider issue 2. The prior feedback explicitly says \"raw-hex acceptance gate scoped to NEW + allowed paths only.\" This was incorporated into the plan context. The plan's acceptance section says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — this is a shorthand for the scoped check. The prior feedback already established the scoping. So maybe this is already addressed by the prior feedback and I shouldn't re-raise it. The HISTORY says this was incorporated. So the acceptance gate IS scoped — the plan just states the expected result concisely. I think this is actually fine given the prior feedback context. Let me drop this.\n\nBut then I only have the nuxt.config.ts theme-color issue. Is that medium? The theme-color affects the browser chrome / status bar color on mobile. If it mismatches the actual background, there's a visible color seam. For a Capacitor mobile app, this matters. The plan changes --bg but doesn't update theme-color. nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch. This is a real medium.\n\nActually, let me also think about whether there are other issues I'm missing.\n\n29. **main.scss @use and tokens.scss :root**: When main.scss does `@use './tokens.scss'`, the `:root` block in tokens.scss will be emitted. But SCSS `@use` loads the file once. If tokens.scss only contains `:root { ... }` (CSS output), @use will emit it. Good.\n\nBut if tokens.scss uses SCSS variables (with `$`), those wouldn't be available in main.scss unless forwarded. The plan says tokens.scss has \"Semantic aliases via var()\" — these are CSS custom properties, not SCSS variables. So @use just emits the CSS. OK.\n\n30. **tokens.scss as a SCSS partial**: The filename is `tokens.scss`. With `@use './tokens.scss'`, SCSS looks for the file. If it's named `tokens.scss` (not `_tokens.scss`), @use can still load it directly. OK. Actually, `@use './tokens.scss'` with the full extension works. But `@use './tokens'` would also work and SCSS would find `tokens.scss`. The plan says `@use './tokens.scss'` — fine.\n\n31. Let me reconsider whether the plan is complete for the \"visual foundation\" task. The task is to establish the visual foundation. The plan creates tokens, brand assets, scatter layout, visual state mapping, Logo, VisualBackground, and wires them into main.scss and app.vue. This is comprehensive. OK.\n\n32. **Does the plan handle the `--stroke` token?** The plan defines `--stroke #30364A`. But the old main.scss doesn't have `--stroke`. The contract doesn't mention stroke. This is a new token. Where is it used? The plan doesn't say. But it's a design token — it's fine to define it for future use. Not an issue.\n\n33. Let me reconsider the tsx self-check pattern more carefully. The plan says scatter.ts has \"Self-check via assert + `if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))`\". This pattern: when you run `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`, `process.argv[1]` is the path to the script, and `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` is also the script path. They should match. The assert block runs validation logic. If the assert passes, the script exits cleanly. This is a valid pattern. OK.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: `process.argv[1]` might be the absolute path while `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` is also absolute. They should match if tsx resolves them consistently. OK, this works.\n\n34. One more thing: the plan says `apps/mobile/visual.ts — export * from \"../../shared/visual\"`. But `shared/visual/index.ts` re-exports 3 modules (assets, scatter, visual-state). So `apps/mobile/visual.ts` would export everything from these 3 modules. If there are naming conflicts between modules... assets.ts exports LOGO_FILE, MAGIC_SVG_FILES, BRAND_ASSET_BASE, FALLBACK_DECOR. scatter.ts exports ScatterItem, scatterLayout. visual-state.ts exports FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE, ACCENT_CATALOG, visualStateToCssVars. No conflicts. OK.\n\n35. **VisualBackground imports SVG files**: \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". In Nuxt/Vite, importing an SVG gives a URL string. But for mask: url(...), you need the URL. `import sparkUrl from '~/assets/brand/magic-spark.svg'` returns the URL. Then `mask: url(v-bind(sparkUrl))` or inline style. This works. But the plan says VisualBackground renders \"positioned <span> mask SVGs\". Each span would need its own SVG URL. With 6 SVGs, VisualBackground would import all 6. The scatter layout determines which SVG goes at which position. The asset field in ScatterItem maps to the SVG name. VisualBackground needs a mapping from asset name → imported URL. This could be a record like `{ 'magic-spark': sparkUrl, ... }`. This is implementation detail — the plan covers the approach. OK.\n\nI think the main issue is the nuxt.config.ts theme-color. Let me also check if there's a concern about the `--bg` change affecting the `body` background. The main.scss has `body { background: var(--bg); }`. With --bg changing to #0D0F17, the body background changes. The theme-color in nuxt.config.ts stays at #0e0f12. This creates a mismatch. Medium.\n\nActually, I realize there might be one more issue: the plan says `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`. But the static `:root` in tokens.scss would define `--accent: #7dd3fc`. At runtime, visualStateToCssVars would override --accent with the catalog value. But where is visualStateToCssVars applied? The plan doesn't specify where the CSS vars from visualStateToCssVars are injected into the DOM. Presumably this is P11/P12 (when VisualState is fetched from backend). In P09, the static --accent in tokens.scss serves as the default. This is fine — the plan is establishing the foundation, and runtime overrides come later. OK.\n\nLet me finalize. I have one solid medium issue:\n\n1. [medium] theme-color-mismatch @## Wiring (nuxt.config.ts) → update theme-color meta from #0e0f12 to new --bg #0D0F17 since nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch paths\n\nActually, is this really medium or just a nit? The theme-color meta affects the browser chrome. For a Capacitor app, the WebView might not even show a browser chrome (it's a native app). In Capacitor, the app is full-screen within the WebView. The theme-color meta might not be relevant in a Capacitor context. Hmm.\n\nBut it's still a factual inconsistency — the design system changes --bg but leaves a hardcoded reference to the old value. And the plan's acceptance says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — but nuxt.config.ts would have `#0e0f12` (raw hex) which is NOT in the allowed list. Wait — the prior feedback says pre-existing raw hex in nuxt.config.ts... actually nuxt.config.ts wasn't mentioned in the prior feedback's out-of-scope list (it mentioned tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue). nuxt.config.ts IS in MAY touch paths. So the plan COULD update it. And the acceptance claim \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" would be violated by nuxt.config.ts having `#0e0f12`.\n\nThis is actually the stronger framing: the acceptance gate says raw hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets, but nuxt.config.ts (which is in MAY touch paths) has raw hex `#0e0f12` that the plan doesn't touch. If the plan claims raw-hex only in those 3 locations, nuxt.config.ts violates that claim. The plan should either update the theme-color to reference a var (can't, it's a meta tag — needs a literal) or move it... actually meta tags need literal hex values, you can't use CSS vars in `<meta name=\"theme-color\" content=\"...\">`. So the plan should update the literal to #0D0F17 and acknowledge it in the acceptance scoping.\n\nSo the issue is:\n- nuxt.config.ts theme-color has raw hex #0e0f12, which is neither in the allowed raw-hex files list nor updated by the plan. This both creates a stale color AND violates the stated acceptance gate.\n\nThis is medium. Let me also think about whether the acceptance gate wording already covers this. The prior feedback says \"raw-hex acceptance gate scoped to NEW + allowed paths only; pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope.\" nuxt.config.ts is NOT listed as out of write-scope (it's in MAY touch). So the plan should handle nuxt.config.ts's raw hex. But it doesn't.\n\nOK, I'm confident this is a medium issue. Let me check if there are other issues.\n\n36. Let me reconsider: the plan says `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`. This raw hex is in tokens.scss, which is an allowed raw-hex file. OK.\n\n37. The plan mentions `--error->danger, --ok->mana` as legacy aliases. So `--error` becomes `var(--danger)` and `--ok` becomes `var(--mana)`. The old main.scss had `--error: #ff5c5c` and `--ok: #3fd07a`. The new tokens have `--danger: #FF6B7A` and `--mana: #8FD7C7`. So the legacy aliases remap to the new palette. Components using `var(--error)` would now get `#FF6B7A` instead of `#ff5c5c`. This is a color change but it's intentional (new palette). OK.\n\n38. Let me see if there are any issues with the VisualBackground component. The plan says it's ~90 LOC SFC. It uses `getComputedStyle` in `onMounted`. This requires `onMounted` from Vue. It reads `--reduced-motion` from the document. If the var isn't set, getComputedStyle returns empty string, and the `reduced` ref would be falsy. This is fine.\n\nThe plan says VisualBackground reads `--brand-decoration-primary/muted tokens` for color via currentColor. This means the SVG mask spans use `color: var(--brand-decoration-primary)` and the mask is filled with currentColor. This works with CSS masks. OK.\n\n39. I think I have enough. Let me also quickly verify there are no critical issues. The plan doesn't introduce Math.random (uses LAYOUT_TABLE). No Google Fonts. No security issues. Files within 150 LOC. VisualState fields match the contract. OK.\n\nLet me finalize with the nuxt.config.ts theme-color issue as the single medium issue.\n\nWait, actually, let me reconsider the severity. The acceptance gate explicitly says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\" nuxt.config.ts has `#0e0f12` (line 31). nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch paths. The plan doesn't touch it. So:\n1. The acceptance claim is false (nuxt.config.ts has raw hex not in the allowed list).\n2. The theme-color is stale (doesn't match new --bg).\n\nThis could be high if we consider the acceptance gate violation as violating a stated criterion. The acceptance criterion is \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — and the plan fails this criterion because nuxt.config.ts has raw hex that's neither in the allowed files nor touched by the plan.\n\nHmm, but the prior feedback says \"pre-existing committed raw hex ... is out of write-scope.\" The prior feedback specifically mentions tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue but NOT nuxt.config.ts. nuxt.config.ts is in MAY touch. So either:\n- The plan should update nuxt.config.ts theme-color to #0D0F17 (removing the stale hex and matching the new palette)\n- Or the plan should explicitly list nuxt.config.ts as having pre-existing raw hex that's out of scope\n\nNeither is done. So this is a gap. I'll rate it medium — it's not catastrophic, but it's a real defect in the acceptance gate and a stale color reference.\n\nLet me also consider: is there a `--stroke` token being newly introduced but the old main.scss doesn't have it, and no existing component uses it? That's fine — it's a new token for future use.\n\nLet me check one more thing — does the plan mention updating tailwind.config.ts? No, and it's not in allowed paths. The plan acknowledges tailwind is P10. OK.\n\nActually, I want to check one more concern: the plan says tokens.scss has `--font-sans (local stack)`. The old main.scss also has `--font-sans` with a local stack. The plan moves this to tokens.scss. Fine.\n\nI'll go with the single medium issue about nuxt.config.ts theme-color / acceptance gate scoping.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider whether this is truly medium or if I'm overthinking it. The prior feedback's round 1 already established the scoping of the raw-hex gate. The plan's acceptance section is a concise restatement. The nuxt.config.ts theme-color is a meta tag that needs a literal hex value — you can't use var() in a meta tag. So even if the plan touches nuxt.config.ts, it would still have raw hex there. The acceptance gate \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" literally cannot be satisfied if nuxt.config.ts needs a literal theme-color. So either:\n- The acceptance gate needs to also allow nuxt.config.ts for theme-color\n- Or the plan should note this exception\n\nThis is a real gap in the acceptance criteria. The plan's acceptance claim is provably unsatisfiable as stated. That's medium.\n\nOK, I'm going with one medium issue. Let me formulate it.\n\n`[medium]acceptance-miss @## Acceptance → nuxt.config.ts theme-color #0e0f12 is stale vs new --bg #0D0F17 and is raw-hex outside the allowed file list; update it to #0D0F17 or exempt nuxt.config.ts in the raw-hex gate`\n\nHmm, that's a bit long. Let me tighten it.\n\n`[medium]acceptance-miss @## Acceptance → update nuxt.config.ts theme-color from #0e0f12 to #0D0F17 (new --bg); it is in MAY-touch paths and its raw hex violates the stated raw-hex gate`\n\nThat's better. Let me count characters: about 160 chars. Within 120 for the fix part? The fix is \"update nuxt.config.ts theme-color from #0e0f12 to #0D0F17 (new --bg); it is in MAY-touch paths and its raw hex violates the stated raw-hex gate\" — that's about 140 chars. Slightly over. Let me trim.\n\n`[medium]acceptance-miss @## Acceptance → update nuxt.config.ts theme-color #0e0f12 → #0D0F17 to match new --bg; its raw hex violates the stated raw-hex gate`\n\nFix part: \"update nuxt.config.ts theme-color #0e0f12 → #0D0F17 to match new --bg; its raw hex violates the stated raw-hex gate\" — ~100 chars. OK.\n\nActually, I want to double-check — is the theme-color truly going to be visible/stale? In a Capacitor app, the status bar color is often controlled by Capacitor plugins (e.g., @capacitor/status-bar), not the theme-color meta tag. But the plan doesn't mention Capacitor status bar configuration. The theme-color meta is still present in nuxt.config.ts and would be stale. Even if it's not visible in the final native app, it's a factual inconsistency. And the acceptance gate violation is real. Medium is appropriate.\n\nLet me finalize my verdict. One medium issue, so ok: false.\n\nActually, hold on. Let me reconsider if this is truly medium or if I should accept. The prior feedback from round 1 was incorporated and the plan is a revised version. The prior feedback specifically scoped the raw-hex gate to \"NEW + allowed paths only\" and mentioned tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue as out of scope. nuxt.config.ts was NOT mentioned. The plan leaves nuxt.config.ts untouched.\n\nThe question is: does the plan's acceptance section accurately describe a verifiable gate? \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — this is the expected state after the plan. But nuxt.config.ts (MAY touch) has raw hex #0e0f12. This is neither touched by the plan nor listed as an exception. So the acceptance claim is inaccurate.\n\nI think this is a legitimate medium issue. The plan should either update the theme-color or add nuxt.config.ts to the exception list in the acceptance criteria.\n\nLet me go with this. Final verdict: ok: false, one medium issue.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-b3f97c5dfaa9e944","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /usr/projects/Диплом && rg -n \"#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,6}\\b\" apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts 2>/dev/null; echo \"===\"; rg -n \"theme-color|content:\" apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts; echo \"===\"; rg -ln \"fonts.googleapis\\|gstatic\" apps/ shared/ -g '!node_modules' 2>/dev/null; echo \"done\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"polza","model":"z-ai/glm-5.2","usage":{"input":14207,"output":9634,"cacheRead":256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24097,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782865665198,"responseId":"gen_2183393871734640641"},"timestamp":"2026-07-01T00:28:57.715Z","cwd":"/usr/projects/Диплом"}
