{"isSidechain":true,"agentId":"2d5be40f-7ed8-4fd","type":"assistant","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me now check the plan's claims about the visualStateToCssVars function output variables - it mentions `--task-button-text`, `--task-list-heading`, `--level-up-text`, `--empty-state-text`, `--reduced-motion`. But the VisualState type has `task_button_text`, `task_list_heading`, `level_up_text`, `empty_state_text` as string fields. These are text content, not CSS variables. Making them CSS variables doesn't make sense - they're text strings that would need to be rendered as content, not as CSS custom properties. Actually, CSS custom properties CAN hold text content and be used via `content: var(--task-button-text)`. But that's a design choice... let me think about whether this is a real issue or a design choice.\n\nActually wait - looking more carefully: `task_button_text`, `task_list_heading`, `level_up_text`, `empty_state_text` are string values from the backend VisualState. The plan says `visualStateToCssVars` returns CSS vars including `--task-button-text`, `--task-list-heading`, `--level-up-text`, `--empty-state-text`. These would be CSS custom properties holding text strings. That's unusual but not wrong - you can use them with `content: var(--task-button-text)`. This seems like a design choice within the plan's scope, not a bug.\n\nNow let me focus on the key issues:\n\n1. **`npx tsx` for self-checks** — The plan says to run `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts` and `npx tsx shared/visual/visual-state.ts`. But `tsx` is NOT installed as a dependency in either the root or apps/mobile package.json. The root package.json has no dependencies. The apps/mobile package.json doesn't list tsx. Using `npx tsx` would require downloading it on the fly, which may or may not work depending on network. The self-check blocks use `import.meta.url` + `fileURLToPath` + `assert`, but tsx is needed to run .ts files directly. This is a verification issue - the self-check commands might not work.\n\nWait, but actually `npx tsx` would download it. That's what npx does. But it's fragile. And the plan says these are acceptance criteria: \"tsx self-checks pass\". If tsx isn't installed, these can't be verified. But `npx` would install it on the fly. Hmm, let me think about whether this is medium or high. The self-check is a verification step, and if the tool isn't available, it can't be verified. But npx handles this. Actually, this is more of a nit since npx would auto-install. But wait - the acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\" - if there's no tsx installed, this is a problem. Let me check if bun can run TS files...\n\nActually `bun run shared/visual/scatter.ts` would work too! Since bun is installed (v1.3.14). The plan specifies `npx tsx` but bun is available and could run TS files directly. This seems like a verification concern but npx tsx would work. Let me think about severity.\n\nActually, looking at the acceptance criteria more carefully: \"tsx self-checks pass; `cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck` passes\". The plan is using `npx tsx` which would auto-download. That's fine for a one-off. Not a real issue.\n\n2. **Color value mismatch**: The plan's tokens.scss uses `--bg #0D0F17` but the existing main.scss has `--bg: #0e0f12` and nuxt.config.ts has `theme-color: #0e0f12`. The plan changes `--bg` from `#0e0f12` to `#0D0F17`. This is a different color. Is this intentional? The plan says it's creating new canonical color tokens. But `theme-color` meta tag in nuxt.config.ts still says `#0e0f12`. If --bg changes to #0D0F17, the theme-color meta tag should match. However, nuxt.config.ts is in the \"MAY touch\" list, so they could update it. But the plan doesn't mention updating the theme-color meta tag. This is a real inconsistency - the visual background color changes but the browser chrome color doesn't.\n\nWait, is this actually medium+? The plan doesn't mention updating the theme-color meta. If they change --bg to #0D0F17, the theme-color in nuxt.config.ts will still say #0e0f12, which would be a slight mismatch. But the plan says \"MAY touch nuxt.config.ts\" so they could update it. But the plan doesn't mention it. This seems like a missing edge case / incomplete plan. Medium severity.\n\n3. **Tailwind config raw hex**: The plan's acceptance gate says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\" But the plan's prior feedback explicitly acknowledges that pre-existing raw hex in tailwind.config.ts is out of write-scope and left untouched. However, the acceptance gate says \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — this would FAIL because tailwind.config.ts still has raw hex. Wait, the prior feedback says \"raw-hex acceptance gate scoped to NEW + allowed paths only; pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope (P10) and left untouched (not regressed, not introduced by this packet).\" So the acceptance gate is scoped to NEW + allowed paths. That means the acceptance check should be `rg '#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,6}' apps/mobile/app/assets/css/tokens.scss shared/visual/visual-state.ts shared/visual/assets.ts` and check no raw hex in NEW files outside those. That's fine.\n\nBut wait — there's also `main.scss` that currently has raw hex. The plan says to move all raw hex from main.scss to tokens.scss and replace `:root{...}` with `@use './tokens.scss'`. After this, main.scss should have NO raw hex. That's in-scope and the plan handles it. Good.\n\nBut what about AppButton.vue's `color: #fff` and `rgba(124, 92, 255, ...)` in AppButton/BottomNav/AppHeader? These are out of write-scope. The acceptance gate is scoped to NEW + allowed paths. So these pre-existing raw values are OK. Fine.\n\n4. **`--accent-weak` as raw hex #2a2347**: The plan says `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`. This is fine since tokens.scss is the designated raw hex file.\n\n5. **VisualBackground.vue LOC**: Plan says ~90 LOC. The PROJECT_RULES say files ≤150 LOC. 90 is fine.\n\n6. **tokens.scss LOC**: ~115 LOC. Under 150. Fine.\n\n7. **visual-state.ts ~120 LOC**: Under 150. Fine.\n\n8. **scatter.ts ~95 LOC**: Under 150. Fine.\n\n9. **The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--accent`**. The VisualState type has `accent_color: string`. The plan says \"Validate accent ∈ catalog else fallback.\" The ACCENT_CATALOG is in visual-state.ts. This is fine.\n\n10. **Logo.vue import path**: `import logoUrl from '~/assets/brand/chubzik-logo.png'`. The source assets are in `/home/guihal/Стол/Правки/Изображения/logo.png` but the plan says to copy as `chubzik-logo.png`. The source file is `logo.png`, not `chubzik-logo.png`. The plan says to copy 7 assets including `chubzik-logo.png`. But the source file is named `logo.png`. So they're renaming during copy. That's fine as long as the plan is consistent. But wait - the prior feedback says \"copied FROM /home/guihal/Стол/Правки/Изображения/ (logo.png, magic-spark.svg, ...)\". So logo.png → chubzik-logo.png is a rename. That's fine, just needs to be consistent. The Logo.vue imports `chubzik-logo.png`. Consistent. Good.\n\n11. **VisualBackground.vue scatter items**: The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". But the scatterLayout returns ScatterItem with `asset` field. The 6 SVG files are: magic-spark, magic-curl, magic-orbit, magic-thread, magic-wisp, tiny-spark. But the VisualState decorative_detail values are \"soft-sparks\" | \"thin-rings\" | \"small-dots\". The plan says FALLBACK_DECOR='soft-sparks'. The scatterLayout maps detail → ScatterItem[]. So for \"soft-sparks\" it would use spark-related SVGs, for \"thin-rings\" ring/orbit SVGs, for \"small-dots\" dot-related SVGs. But with only 6 SVGs, the mapping needs to make sense. This seems like a design decision within the plan's scope. Not a bug.\n\n12. **Reduced motion handling**: The plan says VisualBackground.vue reads `--reduced-motion` CSS var via getComputedStyle in onMounted. This is a client-side approach. Since ssr: false in nuxt.config.ts, onMounted will always fire. Fine.\n\n13. **The `@use './tokens.scss'` in main.scss**: The plan says to replace `:root{...}` with `@use './tokens.scss'`. But `@use` in SCSS doesn't automatically output the variables to CSS. `@use` loads the module for SCSS variables/mixins, but CSS custom properties defined in tokens.scss inside `:root {}` would still be output IF tokens.scss has `:root { ... }` at the top level. Actually, `@use` includes the CSS output of the used file. So if tokens.scss has `:root { --bg: ...; }`, then `@use './tokens.scss'` in main.scss would output that `:root` block. This is correct behavior.\n\nWait, actually, there's a subtlety. With `@use`, the CSS from the used file is included ONCE, the first time it's used. Since main.scss is the only file using tokens.scss, the `:root` block from tokens.scss will be output. This should work. Good.\n\n14. **Missing `--stroke` in existing code**: The plan introduces `--stroke: #30364A`. The existing code doesn't use `--stroke`. This is a new token, fine.\n\n15. **The plan's `visualStateToCssVars` returns CSS vars**: It returns `--accent, --bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg, --decor-detail, --task-button-text, --task-list-heading, --level-up-text, --empty-state-text, --reduced-motion`. The VisualState field `profile_background` maps to `--profile-bg`. The `background_variant` maps to `--bg-variant`. `card_variant` maps to `--card-variant`. `decorative_detail` maps to `--decor-detail`. These are string values (like \"dark-ember\", \"graphite\", etc.) being put into CSS variables. How would these be consumed? They'd need CSS rules like:\n```css\n[data-bg-variant=\"dark-ember\"] { background: var(--bg-dark-ember); }\n```\nor similar. The plan doesn't describe how the variant CSS vars are consumed by the app. But that's P10/P11 scope probably. The plan is creating the foundation. The tokens.scss defines `--bg-dark-ember`, `--card-graphite`, etc. as raw hex. The visualStateToCssVars sets `--bg-variant: dark-ember` (a string). Some consumer would then need to map `--bg-variant` to `--bg-dark-ember`. But that's not in this plan's scope. Fine.\n\nActually wait - the tokens.scss defines `--bg-dark-ember/--bg-deep-forest/--bg-midnight` etc. as raw hex. But visualStateToCssVars sets `--bg-variant: \"dark-ember\"` (a string). There's no automatic mapping from the string \"dark-ember\" to the var `--bg-dark-ember`. This means the CSS would need something like:\n```css\nbody[data-bg-variant=\"dark-ember\"] { background: var(--bg-dark-ember); }\n```\nBut the plan doesn't mention setting any `data-*` attributes. It just returns CSS vars. If `--bg-variant` is set to the string \"dark-ember\", how does the body background actually change? This seems like a gap, but it's likely P10/P11's job to wire it up. The plan is just creating the foundation (tokens + the function). The function returns the vars, and a future packet would apply them. So this is acceptable for the plan scope.\n\n16. **Self-check with `assert`**: The plan says \"Self-check via assert + `if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))`\". In an ES module context (package.json has `\"type\": \"module\"`), `import.meta.url` is available. `fileURLToPath` needs to be imported from `node:url`. The plan doesn't mention this import. But it's a standard Node.js thing. Not really an issue for a plan - the implementation would handle it.\n\nBut wait - `assert` in Node.js: in ESM, you can use `import assert from 'node:assert'` or `console.assert`. The plan says \"assert\" which could be `node:assert`. Fine.\n\n17. **The plan mentions `process.argv[1]`**: In the root package.json, `\"type\": \"module\"`. So shared/visual/*.ts are ESM. When run with `npx tsx`, `import.meta.url` works. `process.argv[1]` would be the path to the script. `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` would give the same path. This comparison should work. Fine.\n\n18. **Missing tsx dependency**: As discussed, `npx tsx` would auto-install. But actually, looking at the project - it uses bun. Could they use `bun run shared/visual/scatter.ts` instead? Yes. But the plan specifies `npx tsx`. This is a verification concern but npx handles it. Not a real issue.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\". If tsx isn't a dependency and the CI/environment doesn't have network access, this would fail. But in practice, `npx tsx` downloads it. And bun is available and could run TS directly. The plan could use `bun run` instead of `npx tsx`. This is a verification concern. But it's not really wrong - `npx tsx` works. Let me not raise this.\n\n19. **theme-color mismatch**: As I noted in point 2, the plan changes `--bg` from `#0e0f12` to `#0D0F17` but doesn't mention updating the `theme-color` meta tag in nuxt.config.ts (which is `#0e0f12`). The plan says \"MAY touch nuxt.config.ts\" but doesn't include updating theme-color in its task list. This is a real inconsistency. Medium severity.\n\n20. **`--accent` default change**: The existing `--accent` is `#7c5cff` (lilac/purple). The plan changes the default to `#7dd3fc` (light blue, non-lilac). This is intentional per the requirements. But the existing `rgba(124, 92, 255, ...)` values in AppButton.vue, BottomNav.vue, AppHeader.vue are hard-coded RGB equivalents of `#7c5cff`. These are out of write-scope. When the accent changes to `#7dd3fc`, these hardcoded rgba values will be visually inconsistent with the new accent color. But the prior feedback acknowledges these are out of scope (P10). This is a known limitation, not a new issue.\n\n21. **AppButton.vue `color: #fff`**: Raw hex in an out-of-scope file. The acceptance gate is scoped to NEW + allowed paths. Fine.\n\n22. **LOC check**: All files are under 150 LOC per the plan's estimates. Good.\n\n23. **VisualState fields**: The plan says \"VisualState fields fixed (no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed)\". The VisualState type in shared/contracts/visual-settings.ts has: accent_color, background_variant, card_variant, task_button_text, task_list_heading, profile_background, decorative_detail, level_up_text, empty_state_text. The plan's visualStateToCssVars returns vars for these fields. It does NOT add new fields. Good - no OD1/OD2.\n\n24. **No Math.random**: The plan explicitly says scatterLayout uses a fixed LAYOUT_TABLE. No Math.random. Good.\n\n25. **No Google Fonts**: The plan uses local font stack. Good.\n\n26. **The plan says `apps/mobile/visual.ts = export * from \"../../shared/visual\"`**: But the root package.json has `\"type\": \"module\"`. The apps/mobile directory has its own package.json. The path `../../shared/visual` from `apps/mobile/visual.ts` goes to `shared/visual/index.ts`. This should work with Nuxt's module resolution. Actually, does Nuxt/Vite resolve `../../shared/visual` from `apps/mobile/visual.ts`? The Nuxt project root is `apps/mobile`. So `../../shared/visual` goes up to repo root, then into `shared/visual`. This would resolve to `/usr/projects/Диплом/shared/visual/index.ts`. This should work if the Nuxt config or tsconfig includes paths outside the project root. Let me check the tsconfig.\n\nThe tsconfig extends `./.nuxt/tsconfig.json`. The Nuxt-generated tsconfig may or may not include paths to `../../shared`. But the existing `apps/mobile/api.ts` already does `export * from \"../../shared/api\"`, which works. So `apps/mobile/visual.ts` following the same pattern should work too. Good.\n\n27. **shared/visual/index.ts re-exports**: The plan says it re-exports 3 modules (assets.ts, scatter.ts, visual-state.ts). But shared/visual/ doesn't exist yet. The plan creates it. Good.\n\n28. **Logo.vue mask approach**: Using `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))`. In Vue SFC with `<style>`, `v-bind()` in CSS is a Vue 3 feature that works. The `mask` CSS property with a URL... actually, `mask` shorthand with `url()` should work. But there's a question: `mask: url(...)` typically needs `mask-size`, `mask-repeat`, `mask-position` to render correctly. The plan doesn't detail these. But this is a design/implementation detail, not a plan-level issue.\n\nActually, there's a potential issue: CSS `mask` with a PNG file. CSS masking with `mask: url(image.png)` uses the alpha channel of the image as the mask. This means the logo PNG would be used as a mask, and the actual color would come from the element's `background` or `color`. This is a valid technique for theming logos. But if the PNG has its own colors, using it as a mask would only use the alpha channel. This seems intentional for theming (currentColor). Fine for a plan.\n\n29. **VisualBackground.vue LOC ~90**: The plan says it imports each SVG, renders scatter items, handles reduced motion. 90 LOC seems tight but plausible. Under 150. Fine.\n\n30. **The plan's acceptance gate**: \"rg Math.random apps shared none; rg fonts.googleapis|gstatic none; raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\" Wait - \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\" But assets.ts is listed as \"Pure data, no DOM\" with `LOGO_FILE='chubzik-logo.png'` etc. There's no raw hex in assets.ts. And the prior feedback says the acceptance gate is \"scoped to NEW + allowed paths only.\" So the check would be: no NEW raw hex in any file OTHER than tokens.scss and visual-state.ts (and the assets directory which has PNG/SVG files, not code with hex). This is fine.\n\nWait, but main.scss is an allowed path. After the plan's changes, main.scss should have NO raw hex (all moved to tokens.scss). So the acceptance check should pass for main.scss. Good.\n\nLet me now think about what real issues exist:\n\n**Issue 1: theme-color mismatch (medium)**\nThe plan changes `--bg` from `#0e0f12` to `#0D0F17` but doesn't mention updating the `theme-color` meta tag in nuxt.config.ts (currently `#0e0f12`). The nuxt.config.ts is in the \"MAY touch\" list, but the plan doesn't include this update. This creates a visual mismatch between the app background and the browser chrome color.\n\n**Issue 2: tailwind.config.ts still references old colors**\nThe tailwind.config.ts has hard-coded colors like `bg: \"#0e0f12\"`, `accent: \"#7c5cff\"`, etc. These are out of write-scope. But the plan changes the canonical tokens (e.g., --bg from #0e0f12 to #0D0F17, --accent from #7c5cff to #7dd3fc). After this plan, tailwind.config.ts colors won't match the tokens.scss colors. However, the prior feedback acknowledges this is out of scope. And looking at the codebase, Tailwind colors aren't actually used in any Vue components (no bg-bg, text-text, etc. classes found). The Tailwind config colors are vestigial. So this isn't really an issue.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The tailwind config has `accent: \"#7c5cff\"` but the plan changes `--accent` to `#7dd3fc`. If Tailwind generates `text-accent` or `bg-accent` utilities, they'd be the wrong color. But since no components use these utilities (I checked - only `text-grad` class is used, which is defined in main.scss), this is not a practical issue. And it's explicitly out of scope.\n\n**Issue 3: The plan doesn't mention what happens with `--error` and `--ok` tokens**\nThe plan says `--error->danger, --ok->mana` as legacy aliases. So `--error: var(--danger)` and `--ok: var(--mana)`. The existing code uses `--error: #ff5c5c` and `--ok: #3fd07a`. The new `--danger: #FF6B7A` and `--mana: #8FD7C7` are different colors. This means `--error` changes from `#ff5c5c` to `var(--danger)` = `#FF6B7A`, and `--ok` changes from `#3fd07a` to `var(--mana)` = `#8FD7C7`. These are color changes that affect existing components. But the plan is explicitly introducing new canonical colors. This is intentional. Not an issue.\n\n**Issue 4: `--bg` value change is a breaking change for existing components**\nThe existing `--bg: #0e0f12` is used by `body { background: var(--bg); }`. Changing it to `#0D0F17` changes the app background color. This is intentional per the plan (new canonical tokens). Not an issue.\n\n**Issue 5: The plan says VisualBackground.vue uses `getComputedStyle` to read `--reduced-motion`**\nBut `--reduced-motion` is a CSS custom property set by visualStateToCssVars. For this to work, the CSS var must be set on some element. The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--reduced-motion`. But where is this applied? The plan doesn't mention where visualStateToCssVars output is applied to the DOM. Is it applied to `:root` or `body`? The plan creates the function but doesn't mention how/where its output is consumed. This is likely P10/P11 scope. But the VisualBackground.vue plan says to read `--reduced-motion` via getComputedStyle, which means it expects the var to be on some parent element. If the var isn't set yet (because no one calls visualStateToCssVars and applies it), the getComputedStyle would return empty. But VisualBackground.vue has a fallback: `@media (prefers-reduced-motion)`. So it has a CSS fallback. And the JS check is an enhancement. This is fine.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the plan: \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via v-bind-less approach: use @media (prefers-reduced-motion) + check --reduced-motion var with getComputedStyle in onMounted → set local reduced ref.\" So the approach is: CSS @media query as primary, plus JS getComputedStyle as enhancement. This is reasonable. But the `--reduced-motion` var comes from visualStateToCssVars which comes from Settings.reduced_motion. The Settings come from the backend. In this packet, there's no wiring to actually fetch Settings and call visualStateToCssVars. So the `--reduced-motion` var won't be set on the DOM in this packet. VisualBackground.vue's getComputedStyle would return empty string, and the `reduced` ref would be falsy. The @media query would still work. So the JS path is a no-op until P10/P11 wires up the settings. This is fine - it's a progressive enhancement.\n\nHmm, actually, the plan also mentions the `Settings` type has `reduced_motion: boolean`. But the plan doesn't say it reads Settings. It says visualStateToCssVars takes `(state, settings?)`. The `settings?` parameter is optional. If no settings, `--reduced-motion` isn't set. This is fine for the foundation packet.\n\nOK, let me also think about whether there are any high or critical issues:\n\n**Potential high issue: Logo.vue `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` might not work**\nActually, CSS `mask` with `url()` pointing to a PNG import... In Vite/Nuxt, importing a PNG gives you a URL string. So `logoUrl` would be something like `/_nuxt/assets/chubzik-logo-abc123.png`. Then `mask: url(/_nuxt/assets/chubzik-logo-abc123.png)` would reference that URL. This should work in modern browsers. But `mask` needs vendor prefixes (`-webkit-mask`) for some browsers. The plan doesn't mention `-webkit-mask`. Since this is a Capacitor app (Android WebView), `-webkit-mask` might be needed. But this is an implementation detail, not a plan-level issue. Actually, for a plan, this level of detail isn't required.\n\n**Potential issue: File count / scope**\nThe plan creates 9 files + copies 7 assets + modifies 2 files (main.scss, app.vue). That's a lot for one packet, but the complexity is \"complex\" so it's expected.\n\nLet me also check if there are any issues with the `@use` approach:\n\n**@use './tokens.scss' behavior**: With Dart Sass (which is what the `sass` package provides), `@use` loads the module and includes its CSS output. If tokens.scss has `:root { ... }`, that `:root` block will be output in the final CSS when main.scss is compiled. This is correct. But there's a subtle issue: if tokens.scss is `@use`d by main.scss, and main.scss is the only entry point (via nuxt.config.ts `css: [\"~/assets/css/main.scss\"]`), then the `:root` block from tokens.scss will be in the output. Good.\n\nBut wait - the plan says \"replace `:root{...}` block with `@use './tokens.scss'`\". So main.scss would have `@use './tokens.scss';` instead of the `:root { ... }` block. The rest of main.scss (body, focus, etc.) stays. This means the `:root` block comes from tokens.scss. Fine.\n\nActually, there might be an issue with `@use` and the ordering of CSS output. With `@use`, the used file's CSS comes BEFORE the using file's CSS. So the output would be:\n1. tokens.scss's `:root { ... }`\n2. main.scss's `* { box-sizing }`, `body { ... }`, etc.\n\nThis is the correct order. Good.\n\nLet me also think about whether the plan's file LOC estimates are realistic:\n- tokens.scss ~115 LOC: With ~25 color tokens, ~10 semantic aliases, ~10 legacy aliases, ~9 variant tints, ~10 non-color tokens, that's ~54 declarations. With comments and `:root { }` wrapper, ~115 LOC is realistic.\n- scatter.ts ~95 LOC: LAYOUT_TABLE with 3 detail types × 6 items each = 18 ScatterItem objects. Each object has 5 fields. That's ~90 lines of data + types + self-check. ~95 LOC seems tight but possible.\n- visual-state.ts ~120 LOC: FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE (~10 fields), ACCENT_CATALOG (~5-10 entries), visualStateToCssVars function (~30 lines), self-check. ~120 LOC seems realistic.\n- Logo.vue ~70 LOC: SFC with script setup + template + style. Reasonable.\n- VisualBackground.vue ~90 LOC: SFC with scatter rendering + reduced motion. Reasonable.\n\nAll under 150 LOC. Good.\n\nLet me now also check: does the plan's `visualStateToCssVars` return `--reduced-motion`? The plan says \"Returns --accent, --bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg, --decor-detail, --task-button-text, --task-list-heading, --level-up-text, --empty-state-text, --reduced-motion.\" Yes. And `--reduced-motion` comes from `settings?.reduced_motion`. If settings is undefined, what's the default? The plan says \"settings?\" is optional. If not provided, `--reduced-motion` probably shouldn't be set, or defaults to something. The plan doesn't specify. But this is an implementation detail.\n\nActually, looking again at the plan: \"Null OR disable_visual_randomness → fallback.\" So if state is null OR settings.disable_visual_randomness is true, it returns FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE vars. The `--reduced-motion` would come from `settings.reduced_motion`. If settings is undefined, maybe it doesn't include `--reduced-motion`. This is fine.\n\nNow, let me think about whether there are any issues I missed:\n\n**Issue: The plan doesn't mention creating `shared/visual/` directory**\nWell, creating files in `shared/visual/` implicitly creates the directory. Not an issue.\n\n**Issue: The plan's `MAGIC_SVG_FILES` list**\nThe plan says `MAGIC_SVG_FILES=['magic-spark',...6]`. The 6 SVG files are: magic-spark, magic-curl, magic-orbit, magic-thread, magic-wisp, tiny-spark. So MAGIC_SVG_FILES would be `['magic-spark', 'magic-curl', 'magic-orbit', 'magic-thread', 'magic-wisp', 'tiny-spark']`. That's 6 files. But the plan says \"6 svg\" and names them. This is fine.\n\nWait - the plan says \"MAGIC_SVG_FILES=['magic-spark',...6]\". The \"6\" might mean 6 files. And the source has 6 SVGs. Consistent. Good.\n\n**Issue: The plan says \"copy 7 assets (chubzik-logo.png + 6 svg)\"**\n7 = 1 PNG + 6 SVG. Source has logo.png + 6 SVGs. Renaming logo.png to chubzik-logo.png. Consistent. Good.\n\n**Issue: VisualBackground.vue imports SVGs**\nThe plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". In Nuxt/Vite, importing an SVG file gives you the URL. So `import sparkUrl from '~/assets/brand/magic-spark.svg'` would give the URL. Then using it as `mask: url(...)` or `background: url(...)`. This should work with Vite's asset handling. Fine.\n\nBut wait - with 6 SVG files, importing each one individually would be 6 import statements. The plan's VisualBackground.vue at ~90 LOC with 6 imports + scatter rendering + reduced motion... that's plausible.\n\nActually, there's a design question: the scatterLayout returns ScatterItem[] with `asset` field (string). The VisualBackground.vue needs to map the asset string to the imported URL. This could be done with a lookup object:\n```ts\nconst svgUrls = {\n  'magic-spark': sparkUrl,\n  'magic-curl': curlUrl,\n  ...\n}\n```\nThis is an implementation detail. Fine for a plan.\n\n**Issue: The plan says `--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)`**\nThe ACCENT_CATALOG in visual-state.ts has raw hex values. The default accent is `#7dd3fc`. But the plan also says `--accent` is set by visualStateToCssVars based on `state.accent_color`. If the accent_color is in the catalog, use it; else fallback. The fallback would use a default accent. What's the default accent in the fallback? The plan says `--accent default #7dd3fc`. So the fallback accent is `#7dd3fc`. Fine.\n\nBut wait - the tokens.scss also defines `--accent: #7dd3fc` as the default. And visualStateToCssVars would override `--accent` with the runtime value. So tokens.scss provides the default, and visualStateToCssVars provides the runtime override. This is the correct layering. Good.\n\nOK, I think I've found one real medium issue:\n\n1. **theme-color meta tag mismatch**: The plan changes `--bg` to `#0D0F17` but doesn't update the `theme-color` meta tag in nuxt.config.ts (currently `#0e0f12`). This creates a visual mismatch.\n\nAre there any other issues? Let me think harder...\n\n**Issue: The plan doesn't specify how visualStateToCssVars output is applied to the DOM**\nThe function returns `Record<string, string>`. But nothing in this packet applies these CSS vars to the DOM. The VisualBackground.vue reads `--reduced-motion` via getComputedStyle, but nothing sets it. This means the CSS vars from visualStateToCssVars are computed but not applied. Is this a problem? The plan is a \"visual foundation\" packet. It creates the infrastructure (tokens, function, components). The actual application of visualStateToCssVars to the DOM would be in a later packet (P10/P11) when Settings/VisualState are fetched from the backend. This is acceptable scope for a foundation packet.\n\nBut VisualBackground.vue reading `--reduced-motion` via getComputedStyle when nothing sets it... The plan says the component uses `@media (prefers-reduced-motion)` as the primary mechanism, with the CSS var check as an enhancement. So it's fine - the CSS @media query works without the var.\n\n**Issue: The plan says \"rg Math.random apps shared none\" as acceptance**\nBut shared/api/ might have files. Let me check if there's any Math.random already in the codebase.\n\nActually, the acceptance gate is checking that the NEW code doesn't introduce Math.random. If there's existing Math.random in the codebase, the check would fail. Let me verify...\n\nActually I can't run `rg Math.random` because the shared/visual/ files don't exist yet. The check is for the implementation phase, not the plan phase. For the plan, I just need to verify the plan doesn't use Math.random. The plan explicitly says \"fixed LAYOUT_TABLE\" and \"NO Math.random\". Good.\n\n**Issue: Does the plan handle the `--stroke` token?**\nThe existing code doesn't have `--stroke`. The plan introduces `--stroke: #30364A`. No existing code references `--stroke`. The plan is adding it as a new token for future use. Fine.\n\nLet me also check: are there any issues with the file paths in the plan?\n\n- `apps/mobile/app/assets/css/tokens.scss` — in allowed write paths ✓\n- `apps/mobile/app/assets/brand/` — in allowed write paths ✓\n- `shared/visual/assets.ts` — in allowed write paths (shared/visual/**) ✓\n- `shared/visual/scatter.ts` — ✓\n- `shared/visual/visual-state.ts` — ✓\n- `shared/visual/index.ts` — ✓\n- `apps/mobile/visual.ts` — hmm, is this in the allowed write paths? The allowed paths say: shared/visual/**, apps/mobile/app/assets/**, apps/mobile/app/components/Logo.vue, apps/mobile/app/components/VisualBackground.vue, apps/mobile/app/assets/css/tokens.scss, MAY touch apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts / apps/mobile/app/app.vue / apps/mobile/app/assets/css/main.scss.\n\n`apps/mobile/visual.ts` is NOT in the allowed write paths! It's at `apps/mobile/visual.ts`, not under `apps/mobile/app/` or `shared/visual/`. The allowed paths are:\n- shared/visual/** ✓\n- apps/mobile/app/assets/** ✓\n- apps/mobile/app/components/Logo.vue ✓\n- apps/mobile/app/components/VisualBackground.vue ✓\n- apps/mobile/app/assets/css/tokens.scss ✓\n- MAY touch: apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts, apps/mobile/app/app.vue, apps/mobile/app/assets/css/main.scss\n\n`apps/mobile/visual.ts` is NOT listed. But it's mirroring `apps/mobile/api.ts` which already exists. Hmm, is this a scope violation?\n\nWait, looking at the allowed paths more carefully: the PLAN says \"7. apps/mobile/visual.ts — `export * from '../../shared/visual'`.\" But the ALLOWED WRITE PATHS listed at the top don't include `apps/mobile/visual.ts`. This is a real issue - the plan proposes creating a file outside the allowed write paths.\n\nBut wait - the prior feedback (round 1) already established that `apps/mobile/visual.ts = export * from \"../../shared/visual\"` (mirror api.ts). And the ALLOWED WRITE PATHS say \"shared/visual/**, apps/mobile/app/assets/**, ...\". It doesn't include `apps/mobile/visual.ts`. But the prior feedback explicitly endorsed this file. And `apps/mobile/api.ts` exists as a precedent. Is `apps/mobile/visual.ts` implicitly allowed?\n\nActually, looking at the prompt again: \"ALLOWED WRITE PATHS: shared/visual/**, apps/mobile/app/assets/**, apps/mobile/app/components/Logo.vue, apps/mobile/app/components/VisualBackground.vue, apps/mobile/app/assets/css/tokens.scss, MAY touch apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts / apps/mobile/app/app.vue / apps/mobile/app/assets/css/main.scss.\"\n\n`apps/mobile/visual.ts` is not listed. This is a high-severity issue - the plan proposes creating a file outside the allowed write paths. Unless the prior feedback's endorsement of this file overrides the allowed paths list... The prior feedback says \"apps/mobile/visual.ts = export * from '../../shared/visual' (mirror api.ts).\" This was from round 1 feedback that was \"incorporated.\" So the parent orchestrator accepted this. Maybe the allowed paths were expanded implicitly. But strictly speaking, the allowed write paths don't include it.\n\nHmm, but the prior feedback was the HISTORY from round 1. The parent marked it as incorporated. So `apps/mobile/visual.ts` was already approved in round 1. The ALLOWED WRITE PATHS might not have been updated to include it, but the plan's history shows it was approved. I think this is OK - the parent accepted it in round 1.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"Prior feedback incorporated: ... - apps/mobile/visual.ts = export * from '../../shared/visual' (mirror api.ts).\" This means in round 1, the critic (or parent) noted that apps/mobile/visual.ts should mirror api.ts. And it was incorporated into the revised plan. So the parent has effectively approved this path. The ALLOWED WRITE PATHS might be the original set, and the prior feedback expanded it. I'll consider this addressed.\n\nLet me think about whether there are any other issues...\n\n**Issue: The plan mentions \"ponytail: comment on legacy aliases\" in tokens.scss**\nWhat does \"ponytail\" mean? Looking at the existing code, AppHeader.vue has a comment \"// ponytail: placeholder numbers\". So \"ponytail\" seems to be a project convention for marking TODO/placeholder items. The plan uses it in tokens.scss. Fine.\n\n**Issue: Self-check verification commands**\nThe plan says \"Run: `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`\" and \"run `npx tsx shared/visual/visual-state.ts`\". But tsx is not installed. Using `npx tsx` would download it. However, since bun is available, `bun run shared/visual/scatter.ts` would work without downloading anything. The plan's verification commands use `npx tsx` which may fail in environments without network access. But the acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\" — if tsx can't be installed, the acceptance gate fails.\n\nActually, looking at the acceptance criteria: \"Acceptance: tsx self-checks pass; `cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck` passes; rg Math.random apps shared none; rg fonts.googleapis|gstatic none; raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets.\"\n\nThe acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\". If tsx isn't available and npx can't download it, this gate fails. But in practice, npx handles this. And bun could be used as an alternative. I think this is a minor verification concern, not a real issue. The plan specifies the tool and command. Whether it works depends on the environment.\n\nActually, I just realized: the plan says to run self-checks with `npx tsx`. But the acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\". These self-checks use `assert` statements. In Node.js, `assert` from `node:assert` throws AssertionError on failure, which would cause a non-zero exit code. If the self-check passes, exit code is 0. This is a valid verification approach.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue: the plan says \"Self-check via assert + `if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))`\". This means the self-check only runs when the file is executed directly (not when imported). When run with `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`, `process.argv[1]` would be the path to scatter.ts, and `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` would also be the path to scatter.ts. So the comparison would be true, and the self-check would run. Good.\n\nBut wait - `process.argv[1]` when run with `npx tsx` might be the path to the tsx executable, not the script. Let me think... Actually no, with tsx (which is like ts-node), `process.argv[1]` is the script path, not the tsx executable path. tsx is a runtime that transpiles and runs the script. So `process.argv[1]` would be the script path. But `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` gives the absolute path. `process.argv[1]` might be a relative path if invoked as `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`. So the comparison might fail if one is relative and the other is absolute.\n\nHmm, this is a potential issue. If `process.argv[1]` is `shared/visual/scatter.ts` (relative) and `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` is `/usr/projects/Диплом/shared/visual/scatter.ts` (absolute), they won't match. The self-check wouldn't run, and the assert statements wouldn't execute. The command would exit with code 0 (no error), giving a false positive.\n\nActually, `process.argv[1]` with tsx... let me think. When you run `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`, tsx resolves the path. In Node.js, `process.argv[1]` is typically the absolute path to the main module. But with tsx, it might differ. This is uncertain.\n\nA safer approach would be `path.resolve(process.argv[1]) === fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)`. But the plan says `process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` without path.resolve. This could fail if the paths aren't both absolute.\n\nIs this a real issue? It depends on how tsx handles paths. In many cases, tsx normalizes `process.argv[1]` to an absolute path. But it's not guaranteed. This is a potential verification gap - the self-check might silently not run.\n\nHmm, but this is getting into implementation details. The plan is at the planning level. The plan says \"Self-check via assert + `if (process.argv[1]===fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))`\". Whether this works correctly depends on the implementation. If it doesn't work, the acceptance gate \"tsx self-checks pass\" would be a false positive (the command exits 0 but the assert never ran). This is a verification concern.\n\nActually, I think this IS a real issue. If the path comparison fails, the self-check is silently skipped, and the verification gives a false positive. The fix is to use `path.resolve()` on both sides or use a different approach (like `import.meta.main` in Bun, or just always run the assert). But since the plan specifies the exact comparison without path normalization, and this is a known footgun, I should raise it.\n\nSeverity: medium. The self-check might silently not run, giving false confidence. But it's not catastrophic - the code would still work when imported; only the verification is unreliable.\n\nWait, actually, let me reconsider. With `npx tsx`, the tsx runner typically sets `process.argv[1]` to the absolute path of the script. And `fileURLToPath(import.meta.url)` also returns the absolute path. So they should match. The comparison would work. I'm not sure this is actually a problem. Let me not raise it, as it's uncertain and implementation-specific.\n\nLet me also think about: does the plan address the TASK? The TASK is \"P09-1 (visual foundation)\". The plan creates the visual foundation: tokens, scatter layout, visual state mapping, logo component, visual background component, and wiring. This addresses the task. Good.\n\nOK so after thorough analysis, the issues I've found:\n\n1. **theme-color meta tag mismatch (medium)**: Plan changes `--bg` to `#0D0F17` but doesn't update `theme-color` meta in nuxt.config.ts (currently `#0e0f12`).\n\nLet me see if there's anything else...\n\n**Issue: The plan says `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`**\nThe prior feedback says \"tokens.scss keeps --accent-weak legacy token (used by P10 login.vue/FormField.vue/tailwind).\" The plan defines `--accent-weak: #2a2347` as raw hex in tokens.scss. This is fine since tokens.scss is the designated raw hex file. But the prior feedback also says it's used by tailwind.config.ts (`\"accent-weak\": \"#2a2347\"`). The tailwind config has its own raw hex copy. This is out of scope. Fine.\n\nActually, I realize there might be another issue. Let me check the `rgba(124, 92, 255, ...)` values in the existing components. These are hard-coded in AppButton.vue, BottomNav.vue, and AppHeader.vue. The RGB values 124, 92, 255 correspond to #7c5cff (the old accent). The plan changes the accent to #7dd3fc (RGB 125, 211, 252). These hard-coded rgba values won't match the new accent. But these files are out of write-scope (P10). The prior feedback acknowledges this. So it's a known limitation, not a new issue.\n\nLet me also check if the plan's acceptance criteria are verifiable:\n- \"tsx self-checks pass\" — verifiable by running the commands ✓\n- \"`cd apps/mobile && bun run typecheck` passes\" — verifiable ✓ (currently exits 0)\n- \"rg Math.random apps shared none\" — verifiable ✓\n- \"rg fonts.googleapis|gstatic none\" — verifiable ✓\n- \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\" — verifiable ✓ (scoped to NEW + allowed paths)\n\nThe acceptance criteria are verifiable. Good.\n\nWait, I want to double-check one thing: the plan says tokens.scss will have ~115 LOC. Let me count the proposed content:\n- ~14 canonical color tokens\n- ~10 semantic aliases\n- ~10 legacy aliases\n- ~9 variant tints\n- ~10 non-color tokens (radius, space, font, etc.)\nTotal: ~53 declarations + comments + `:root {}` wrapper\n\nWith comments and formatting, 115 LOC is realistic. Under 150. Good.\n\nI think the only real issue I found is the theme-color mismatch. Let me consider if it's really medium or if I'm being too strict.\n\nThe `theme-color` meta tag affects the browser chrome color (address bar in mobile browsers). If `--bg` changes from `#0e0f12` to `#0D0F17`, the app background changes, but the browser chrome stays `#0e0f12`. The difference is subtle (#0e0f12 vs #0D0F17) but it's still a mismatch. And nuxt.config.ts is in the \"MAY touch\" list. The plan just doesn't mention updating it. This is a missing step - medium severity.\n\nActually, is #0D0F17 really different from #0e0f12? Let me compare:\n- #0D0F17 = rgb(13, 15, 23)\n- #0e0f12 = rgb(14, 15, 18)\n\nYes, they're different colors. The difference is subtle but real. The theme-color should match the app background. This is a real issue.\n\nHmm, but actually - is the theme-color supposed to match --bg? Not necessarily. The theme-color is the browser chrome color, which could be different from the app background. But conventionally, they match. And the current code has them matching (#0e0f12 for both). Changing --bg without updating theme-color is an inconsistency. Medium.\n\nActually, I want to also check: does the plan say anything about updating nuxt.config.ts beyond what's in the \"MAY touch\" list? The plan's wiring section says:\n- \"10. main.scss — replace :root{...} block with @use './tokens.scss'\"\n- \"11. app.vue — add <VisualBackground/> as first child inside a relative wrapper\"\n\nIt doesn't mention nuxt.config.ts at all. But nuxt.config.ts is in the \"MAY touch\" list. The plan should mention updating the theme-color if it changes --bg. This is a missing step.\n\nOK, I'm also going to consider one more thing: the plan says \"accent_color: string\" from VisualState is validated against ACCENT_CATALOG. The ACCENT_CATALOG has raw hex values. But the VisualState.accent_color is a string from the backend. What format is it? Is it a hex color? A color name? An ID? Looking at the contract:\n\n```typescript\nexport type VisualState = {\n  accent_color: string;\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nIt's just a string. The plan says \"Validate accent ∈ catalog else fallback.\" So the accent_color string must match a key in the ACCENT_CATALOG. If it doesn't match, use fallback. This is fine. The ACCENT_CATALOG would be something like:\n```typescript\nconst ACCENT_CATALOG = {\n  'sky-blue': '#7dd3fc',\n  'mint-green': '#8FD7C7',\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd `state.accent_color` would be a key like 'sky-blue'. If it's not in the catalog, fallback. This is a reasonable design. Fine.\n\nOK, I think I've been thorough enough. Let me also check one more thing about the `--accent-weak` token. The plan says `--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)`. The existing main.scss has `--accent-weak: #2a2347`. The plan moves this to tokens.scss. But the plan also says `--accent-weak` is a \"Legacy P10-compat utility token via var()\". Wait, the plan says two different things:\n\nIn the canonical tokens section: \"not listed\"\nIn the legacy aliases section: \"--accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here)\"\n\nSo `--accent-weak` is in the legacy aliases section, defined as raw hex #2a2347. But the plan says legacy aliases are \"via var()\". So `--accent-weak: #2a2347` (raw hex) but listed as a legacy alias. This is a contradiction - the plan says legacy aliases use var() but --accent-weak uses raw hex. \n\nWait, let me re-read: \"Legacy P10-compat utility tokens via var(): --accent-grad, --accent-2, --accent-weak (#2a2347 raw — was already raw in old main.scss, keep here), --glow-accent, --ring, --shadow-card, --error->danger, --ok->mana.\"\n\nSo the legacy tokens are \"via var()\" except --accent-weak which is \"#2a2347 raw\". The \"via var()\" applies to most legacy tokens (e.g., --error: var(--danger)), but --accent-weak stays as raw hex because it was already raw and doesn't have a new canonical equivalent. This is fine - it's an exception noted in the plan. The raw hex is in tokens.scss which is the designated raw hex file. No issue.\n\nBut wait - --accent-grad is \"via var()\". The existing --accent-grad is `linear-gradient(135deg, #7c5cff 0%, #4dd4ff 100%)`. If it's \"via var()\", it would be `--accent-grad: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent) 0%, var(--accent-2) 100%)`. But --accent is now #7dd3fc (not #7c5cff) and --accent-2 would be... what? The plan doesn't define --accent-2 in the canonical tokens. Looking at the legacy section: \"--accent-2\" is listed as a legacy token \"via var()\". So --accent-2 would be aliased to something. But what? The plan doesn't say. \n\nHmm, this is getting into implementation details. The plan lists legacy tokens but doesn't specify all their values. For a plan, this level of detail might be sufficient - the implementation would fill in the specifics. But if --accent-2 doesn't have a canonical equivalent, what does it alias to? \n\nLooking at the existing code: `--accent-2: #4dd4ff`. The plan's canonical tokens don't include #4dd4ff. The closest might be `--blue: #7EA7FF`. But that's a different color. So --accent-2 would either need to stay as raw hex #4dd4ff (but the plan says legacy tokens are \"via var()\") or alias to something else. This is a gap in the plan.\n\nBut wait, is this really a medium+ issue? The plan says \"Legacy P10-compat utility tokens via var()\". If --accent-2 can't be expressed via var() because there's no canonical equivalent, it would need to stay as raw hex. But the plan says \"via var()\". This is a minor contradiction. But the plan also says raw hex is allowed in tokens.scss. So even if --accent-2 stays as raw hex in tokens.scss, it's still in the designated raw hex file. The contradiction is about the \"via var()\" label, not about where the raw hex lives. This is a low-severity issue (plan wording inconsistency, not a functional problem). I should drop it.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read more carefully. The plan says:\n- Canonical color tokens include: `--blue #7EA7FF`\n- Legacy aliases via var(): `--accent-2`\n\nIf --accent-2 aliases to --blue (var(--blue)), then --accent-2 would change from #4dd4ff to #7EA7FF. This is a color change. Is this intentional? The plan doesn't specify what --accent-2 aliases to. It could alias to --blue, or it could stay as raw hex. The plan is ambiguous.\n\nBut again, this is an implementation detail. The plan provides the structure (canonical tokens + legacy aliases), and the implementation fills in the mapping. For a plan, this is sufficient. Not a medium+ issue.\n\nLet me finalize. I have one real medium issue:\n\n1. **theme-color meta tag mismatch**: Plan changes `--bg` to `#0D0F17` but doesn't update `theme-color` meta in nuxt.config.ts.\n\nActually, let me reconsider whether this is truly medium. The difference between #0e0f12 and #0D0F17 is very subtle. And the theme-color is a \"nice to have\" for mobile browser chrome. Is this really a \"real defect that is non-trivial to ignore\"? I think so - if you're changing the canonical background color, you should update the browser chrome color too. It's a missing step in the plan. Medium.\n\nAre there any other issues I might have missed? Let me think about the `app.vue` change:\n\n\"11. app.vue — add <VisualBackground/> as first child inside a relative wrapper; keep NuxtLayout/NuxtPage.\"\n\nThe current app.vue is:\n```vue\n<script setup lang=\"ts\">\n</script>\n<template>\n  <NuxtLayout>\n    <NuxtPage />\n  </NuxtLayout>\n</template>\n```\n\nThe plan says to add VisualBackground as the first child inside a relative wrapper. So:\n```vue\n<template>\n  <div class=\"relative-wrapper\">\n    <VisualBackground />\n    <NuxtLayout>\n      <NuxtPage />\n    </NuxtLayout>\n  </div>\n</template>\n```\n\nWait, but VisualBackground is \"fixed full-screen\". If it's `position: fixed`, it doesn't need a relative wrapper. The plan says \"inside a relative wrapper\" but the component is fixed. A fixed element is positioned relative to the viewport, not the relative wrapper. So the relative wrapper is unnecessary for a fixed element. But the plan says to add it. This could be for stacking context (z-index) purposes - to ensure the background is behind the content. But with `position: fixed` and a low z-index, it would be behind everything. The relative wrapper might be for containing the layout flow. This is a design choice, not a bug.\n\nActually, thinking more carefully: if VisualBackground is `position: fixed`, it's taken out of the flow. The relative wrapper would just contain NuxtLayout/NuxtPage normally, with VisualBackground floating behind. This works. The relative wrapper might be unnecessary but not harmful. Fine.\n\nLet me also consider: does the plan mention z-index for VisualBackground? It says \"fixed full-screen\" and \"low opacity\" and \"aria-hidden whole bg\". But doesn't mention z-index. If VisualBackground is fixed without a z-index, it would be at z-index: auto (which is effectively 0). The content would be at z-index: auto too. Depending on DOM order, the background might render on top of content. But since VisualBackground is the first child, it would render behind subsequent siblings at the same z-index. Actually, with position: fixed, the stacking context is different. Fixed elements create a new stacking context. Without z-index, a fixed element would render above non-positioned content but below positioned content with z-index. This could cause the background to render above the content.\n\nWait, actually, the default z-index for a fixed element is `auto`, which means it participates in the normal stacking order. In the normal stacking order, positioned elements (including fixed) are rendered after (on top of) non-positioned elements. So a fixed VisualBackground would render on top of non-positioned content. To fix this, you'd need `z-index: -1` or `z-index: 0` on the background, and `position: relative; z-index: 1` on the content.\n\nThe plan doesn't mention z-index. This could cause the visual background to render on top of the content, making the app unusable. Is this a real issue?\n\nHmm, but the plan says \"fixed full-screen\" and \"low opacity\". If it renders on top with low opacity, it would create a visual overlay but the content would still be partially visible. This is still a usability issue. The background should be behind the content.\n\nActually, I think the plan's mention of \"relative wrapper\" might be intended to address this. If the wrapper has `position: relative` and the background has `z-index: 0` while the content has `z-index: 1`, the background would be behind. But the plan doesn't specify z-index values. This is a gap.\n\nBut is this a plan-level issue or an implementation detail? The plan describes the component as \"fixed full-screen\" with \"low opacity\". The z-index management is an implementation detail that the implementer would handle. But if the plan doesn't mention it, the implementer might miss it. And it's a load-bearing detail for a background component.\n\nI think this is a medium issue - the plan should specify z-index for the background component to ensure it renders behind content. Without it, the background could render on top of content.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. In practice, most CSS resets or frameworks handle this. And a skilled implementer would know to set z-index on a fixed background. The plan describes the component's purpose (background), which implies it should be behind content. The implementer would handle this. I think this is an implementation detail, not a plan-level issue. Let me not raise it.\n\nHmm, but the plan does say \"inside a relative wrapper\". If the wrapper is `position: relative`, and the background is `position: fixed` with no z-index, and the content is inside the same wrapper... the fixed background would still render above the content (since fixed > non-positioned in stacking order). The relative wrapper doesn't help unless z-index is also set. So the plan's mention of \"relative wrapper\" doesn't actually solve the stacking issue. This is a plan-level gap.\n\nBut I'm not sure this is medium+. It depends on whether the implementer would naturally handle z-index. I think most Vue/CSS developers would set z-index on a fixed background. Let me not raise this.\n\nOK, I'll also consider: is the plan's acceptance criteria complete? Let me check:\n- tsx self-checks pass ✓\n- typecheck passes ✓\n- no Math.random ✓\n- no Google Fonts ✓\n- raw hex only in allowed files ✓\n\nIs there anything missing? The plan doesn't mention verifying that the existing components still work (no visual regression). But the plan says it's not touching existing components (except main.scss and app.vue). The main.scss change moves :root to @use tokens.scss. If the token names change (e.g., --bg value changes but name stays), existing components would still work but with new colors. This is intentional. No regression check needed.\n\nActually, wait - the plan changes some token values:\n- --bg: #0e0f12 → #0D0F17\n- --surface: #171a20 → #181B25\n- --surface-2: #1f232b → #222635\n- --