the plan says it's leaving them untouched and not regressing — but the visual result IS a regression (mixed accent colors in shadows). Hmm, but these are pre-existing and out of write scope. The plan correctly scopes. I think this is acceptable but could be flagged as a medium edge-case. Actually, let me reconsider: the plan changes --accent from #7c5cff (lilac) to #7dd3fc (sky). Any component using `var(--accent)` for color/background will change. But components using hardcoded `rgba(124,92,255)` won't. This creates visual inconsistency. The plan doesn't mention this. But fixing it is out of scope (those files are P10). The plan acknowledges P10 is out of scope. I think this is a borderline medium — the plan should at least note the inconsistency risk. But actually the PROJECT_RULES say \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback theme file\" and the rgba(124,92,255) literals violate this. However they're pre-existing and out of write scope. I'll note this as a medium concern about the plan not acknowledging the rgba-lilac divergence, but actually... the prior feedback already addressed this (\"pre-existing committed raw hex in tailwind.config.ts/AppButton.vue is out of write-scope\"). So I should NOT re-raise it.\n\n4. **tsx self-checks via `npx tsx`**: The repo doesn't have tsx installed (no tsx in node_modules, no tsx in package.json). Running `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts` would try to download tsx from npm. This is a real issue — the self-check commands reference a tool that isn't in the project. The plan says \"Run: `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts`\". npx would fetch it, but in an offline environment this would fail. Also, the acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass\". Since tsx isn't a dependency, this is unreliable. Could use `bun run` instead since bun is available. This is a medium issue — the verification command references a tool not in the project's dependency tree.\n\nActually wait — let me reconsider. `npx tsx` will work if there's internet. But this is a build/verification step that should be reproducible. Using `npx tsx` when tsx isn't a devDependency is fragile. Bun is available (`bun --version` → 1.3.14). The plan could use `bun run shared/visual/scatter.ts` instead. This is a real medium issue.\n\n5. **LOC budget**: tokens.scss ~115 LOC (≤150 ✓), scatter.ts ~95 (✓), visual-state.ts ~120 (✓), Logo.vue ~70 (✓), VisualBackground.vue ~90 (✓). All within 150 LOC. Good.\n\n6. **Logo.vue asset name mismatch**: The plan says copy 7 assets including \"chubzik-logo.png\", and Logo.vue imports `~/assets/brand/chubzik-logo.png`. But the SOURCE file is named `logo.png` (not `chubzik-logo.png`). The plan says \"copy 7 assets (chubzik-logo.png + 6 svg)\" — so it's RENAMING logo.png to chubzik-logo.png during copy. That's fine as long as the plan is explicit. The source is logo.png, the destination is chubzik-logo.png. OK, that's consistent within the plan.\n\nWait, but the prior feedback says \"Source assets: copied FROM /home/guihal/Стол/Правки/Изображения/ (logo.png, ...)\". And the assets.ts says `LOGO_FILE='chubzik-logo.png'`. So the copy renames logo.png → chubzik-logo.png. That's fine.\n\n7. **VisualBackground.vue importing SVGs**: The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". But the SVG files are named magic-spark.svg, magic-curl.svg, etc. The scatterLayout has 6 items per detail × 3 details = need multiple SVGs. There are only 6 SVGs + 1 PNG. The plan mentions MAGIC_SVG_FILES=['magic-spark',...6] in assets.ts. The scatter items use `asset` field referencing these SVG names. VisualBackground imports each SVG url. This seems workable.\n\nBut wait — VisualBackground says \"renders scatterLayout(detail) items as positioned <span> mask SVGs (import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg)\". Importing 6 SVGs dynamically by name in Vue requires either static imports or dynamic import. If you do `import sparkUrl from '~/assets/brand/magic-spark.svg'`, you need to know all 6 at compile time. The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\" — this is a dynamic path construction which Vite can't resolve statically. You'd need `import.meta.glob` or static imports. The plan is vague here. This could be a medium issue — the plan doesn't specify HOW to import SVGs (static vs dynamic), and dynamic string interpolation in import paths won't work with Vite.\n\nActually, for 6 known SVGs, you'd use static imports or `import.meta.glob`. The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\" which sounds like static imports for each. But scatterLayout returns asset NAMES as strings, and you need to map those names to imported URLs. You'd need a lookup map: `{ 'magic-spark': sparkUrl, 'magic-curl': curlUrl, ... }`. The plan doesn't mention this mapping. This is a design gap. Medium issue.\n\n8. **visualStateToCssVars return keys vs VisualState fields**: The contract has `profile_background` (not `profile-bg`). The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--profile-bg`. The plan maps `state.profile_background` → `--profile-bg` CSS var. That's fine — the function transforms snake_case fields to kebab CSS vars. But it should map all VisualState fields:\n- accent_color → --accent ✓\n- background_variant → --bg-variant ✓\n- card_variant → --card-variant ✓\n- task_button_text → --task-button-text ✓\n- task_list_heading → --task-list-heading ✓\n- profile_background → --profile-bg ✓\n- decorative_detail → --decor-detail ✓\n- level_up_text → --level-up-text ✓\n- empty_state_text → --empty-state-text ✓\n\nAll 9 VisualState fields are covered. Good. Plus --reduced-motion from settings. Good.\n\n9. **ACcent catalog**: The plan says ACCENT_CATALOG is a const with raw hex in visual-state.ts (allowed as fallback theme file). PROJECT_RULES say \"raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback theme file\". visual-state.ts is described as the fallback theme file. This is allowed. Good.\n\n10. **--accent default #7dd3fc**: The plan says \"--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)\". The PROJECT_RULES say \"no OD1 lilac / OD2 seed\" — so non-lilac is correct. But wait — the current --accent is #7c5cff (lilac). Changing to #7dd3fc is a significant visual change. Is this intentional? The plan says it's \"runtime, from catalog\" — so the default accent comes from ACCENT_CATALOG when state is null/fallback. The FALLBACK_VISUAL_STATE presumably has accent_color = some catalog color. The plan says \"Validate accent ∈ catalog else fallback.\" So if backend returns an accent not in catalog, use fallback. This seems reasonable.\n\n11. **main.scss @use tokens.scss**: The plan says \"replace :root{...} block with @use './tokens.scss'; (SCSS @use)\". But `@use` loads a module — it doesn't inject `:root{}` declarations. If tokens.scss has `:root { ... }` at the top level, then `@use` would include it. But SCSS `@use` doesn't just inline — it loads the module. Actually, if tokens.scss contains `:root { --bg: ...; }` as plain CSS output, then `@use` would include that CSS. But `@use` is designed for mixins/functions/variables, and including a file with `:root {}` via `@use` WILL emit the `:root` block. So this works. But there's a subtlety: `@use` should come before other rules. The plan says \"replace :root{...} block with @use './tokens.scss'\" — so the @use goes at the top, then the body/focus/etc. rules follow. This is fine SCSS-wise.\n\nBut wait — the current main.scss has `--bg: #0e0f12` etc. in `:root`. The plan replaces this with `@use './tokens.scss'` which contains the new `:root { --bg: #0D0F17; ... }`. But the existing main.scss also defines `--font-sans`, `--safe-*` in `:root`. The plan says tokens.scss includes `--font-sans (local stack)` and `--safe-* (env())`. So these move to tokens.scss. Good.\n\nHowever, main.scss line 9 has `--accent-grad: linear-gradient(135deg, #7c5cff 0%, #4dd4ff 100%);` — this has raw hex in the gradient. The plan moves --accent-grad to tokens.scss as a legacy alias via var(). But the gradient currently uses raw hex #7c5cff and #4dd4ff. If tokens.scss redefines --accent-grad using `var(--accent)` and `var(--accent-2)`, that changes the gradient. The plan says \"--accent-grad\" is a legacy alias via var(). So it would be something like `--accent-grad: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent) 0%, var(--accent-2) 100%)`. This means the gradient now uses the new accent (#7dd3fc) instead of lilac. This is a visual change to all components using --accent-grad (AppButton, AppHeader bar-fill, main.scss .text-grad, login brand). This is intentional (non-lilac). OK.\n\n12. **Raw hex in nuxt.config.ts theme-color**: As noted, `content: \"#0e0f12\"` is a raw hex in nuxt.config.ts. The plan MAY touch nuxt.config.ts. The plan doesn't mention updating the theme-color. The raw-hex acceptance gate is \"scoped to NEW + allowed paths only; pre-existing committed raw hex ... is out of write-scope\". nuxt.config.ts is in the MAY-touch list, so it's an allowed path. The pre-existing #0e0f12 was there before. If the plan touches nuxt.config.ts (for other reasons?), the raw hex would be in an allowed path. But the plan doesn't mention touching nuxt.config.ts at all. The theme-color #0e0f12 doesn't match the new --bg #0D0F17. This is a medium issue — the theme-color meta should be updated to match the new --bg value, or the plan should acknowledge leaving it stale.\n\nActually, is nuxt.config.ts one of the \"allowed paths\" for raw hex? The acceptance gate says \"raw-hex only in tokens.scss + visual-state.ts + assets\". nuxt.config.ts isn't in that list. So if the plan touches nuxt.config.ts and leaves #0e0f12 there, that's a raw hex in a non-allowed file. But it's PRE-EXISTING. The prior feedback says \"pre-existing committed raw hex ... is out of write-scope (P10) and left untouched (not regressed, not introduced by this packet).\" But nuxt.config.ts IS in the MAY-touch list. So is the theme-color #0e0f12 pre-existing and left untouched, or should it be updated? The plan doesn't address it. If the plan doesn't touch nuxt.config.ts, then #0e0f12 stays (pre-existing, OK). But the theme-color will be visually wrong (doesn't match new --bg). I'll flag this as medium.\n\n13. **VisualBackground.vue getComputedStyle approach**: The plan says \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via v-bind-less approach: use @media (prefers-reduced-motion) + check --reduced-motion var with getComputedStyle in onMounted → set local reduced ref\". This is reasonable. getComputedStyle on :root to read --reduced-motion. OK.\n\n14. **Missing: VisualBackground doesn't consume VisualState**: VisualBackground.vue takes a `decorativeDetail` prop defaulting to 'soft-sparks'. But how does it get the actual VisualState? The plan says the prop is `VisualState['decorative_detail']`. Presumably the parent (app.vue) would pass the decorative_detail from a VisualState. But app.vue in the plan just says \"add <VisualBackground/> as first child inside a relative wrapper\". It doesn't pass a prop. So VisualBackground uses the default 'soft-sparks'. That's fine for P09 (no backend wired yet). But the plan should be clear that app.vue passes no prop (uses default). OK, that's acceptable.\n\n15. **The plan doesn't mention updating tailwind.config.ts**: As noted, tailwind.config.ts has raw hex (#0e0f12, #171a20, etc.) that diverge from the new tokens.scss hex values. tailwind.config.ts is NOT in the allowed write paths. So the plan can't touch it. But this means Tailwind color utilities would use old values. Since the app barely uses Tailwind color classes (mostly custom CSS with var()), this is low impact. But it's still a divergence the plan should acknowledge. However, it's out of scope, so I'll leave it.\n\n16. **assets.ts BRAND_ASSET_BASE**: \"BRAND_ASSET_BASE path string\" — this is a pure data export. But how will it be used? The Logo.vue imports via `~/assets/brand/chubzik-logo.png` (Nuxt alias), not via BRAND_ASSET_BASE. VisualBackground imports via `~/assets/brand/<name>.svg`. So BRAND_ASSET_BASE in shared/visual/assets.ts might not be used by the mobile app (which uses Nuxt aliases). It could be used by other apps or tests. This is fine — it's pure data.\n\n17. **No mention of `--stroke` token**: The contract doesn't have stroke, but the plan defines `--stroke #30364A`. Currently AppHeader uses `border-bottom: 1px solid var(--surface-2)` not var(--stroke). The plan introduces --stroke as a new token. It's not used by existing code (AppHeader uses --surface-2 for borders). This is fine — it's a new design token for future use.\n\nLet me now compile the issues:\n\n**Issue 1 (medium): npx tsx not a project dependency**\nThe plan's verification commands use `npx tsx shared/visual/scatter.ts` and `npx tsx shared/visual/visual-state.ts`, but tsx is not in package.json or apps/mobile/package.json devDependencies. The repo has bun available. The self-checks should use `bun run` or add tsx as a devDependency. Using `npx tsx` in an offline/CI environment would fail.\n\n**Issue 2 (medium): theme-color meta not updated**\nnuxt.config.ts line 31 has `content: \"#0e0f12\"` which is the OLD --bg value. The new tokens.scss changes --bg to #0D0F17. nuxt.config.ts is in the MAY-touch list. The plan doesn't mention updating theme-color, leaving the browser chrome/status bar showing the wrong color.\n\n**Issue 3 (medium): tokens.scss hex values diverge from tailwind.config.ts**\nThe plan introduces new canonical hex values (--bg #0D0F17, --surface #181B25, etc.) that differ from tailwind.config.ts (#0e0f12, #171a20, etc.). Since tailwind.config.ts is out of write-scope, Tailwind color utilities (bg-bg, text-text, etc.) would use stale values while CSS var() uses new values. The plan doesn't acknowledge this divergence or note that tailwind.config.ts should be updated in P10.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider — is this really a medium? The app doesn't use Tailwind color utilities at all (I searched and found only custom classes). So the divergence has zero practical impact currently. It's a latent inconsistency. But the PROJECT_RULES say raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback file, and tailwind.config.ts has raw hex. The plan can't fix it (out of scope). This is more of a \"known limitation\" than a defect. I'll flag it as medium since the plan creates a palette divergence without acknowledging it.\n\nHmm, actually the tailwind.config.ts hex values are PRE-EXISTING. The plan doesn't change them. The divergence is INTRODUCED by the plan changing the canonical values in tokens.scss to different hex values. If the plan kept the same hex values as tailwind.config.ts, there'd be no divergence. So the plan is CHOOSING to change the palette, creating divergence. This is a real issue.\n\nBut wait — is the palette change intentional? The plan says \"Canonical color tokens (--bg #0D0F17, ...)\". Maybe the designer chose a new palette. The old values (#0e0f12) are very dark blue-black; new (#0D0F17) is similar. Let me check if they're just format differences... #0e0f12 vs #0D0F17 — these are different colors (slightly). #0e0f12 is RGB(14,15,18), #0D0F17 is RGB(13,15,23). Minor difference. #171a20 vs #181B25 — RGB(23,26,32) vs RGB(24,27,37). Again slightly different. #7c5cff vs #7dd3fc — VERY different (lilac vs sky blue). The accent change is intentional (non-lilac per OD1 rule). The bg/surface changes are subtle. So the divergence with tailwind.config.ts is mostly cosmetic for bg/surface but significant for accent. Tailwind's `accent: \"#7c5cff\"` would still show lilac in any Tailwind accent utility. But the app doesn't use Tailwind accent utilities. OK.\n\nI think the main medium issues are:\n1. npx tsx not available\n2. theme-color not updated\n\nLet me also check: does the plan specify what VisualBackground.vue imports for SVGs clearly enough? The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\" — this is ambiguous. In Vite, you can't do `import url from '~/assets/brand/' + name + '.svg'` (dynamic). You need either:\n- Static imports for each: `import spark from '~/assets/brand/magic-spark.svg'` etc.\n- `import.meta.glob('~/assets/brand/*.svg')` \n- A lookup map from name to imported URL\n\nThe plan doesn't specify this. This is a medium design gap that could lead to a non-working component.\n\nLet me also check Logo.vue mask approach: `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` — this uses CSS mask with the imported PNG URL. `mask: url(...)` expects a URL to an image used as mask. For PNG, this creates a luminance/alpha mask. This should work in modern browsers. But `mask` shorthand needs `mask-size`, `mask-repeat` etc. The plan doesn't mention these. This could be a minor issue but probably not medium+.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the Logo.vue approach more carefully. `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` — `v-bind()` in `<style>` works for CSS custom properties and values. But `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` — does Vue's v-bind in style support this syntax? Vue's `v-bind()` in CSS replaces the entire value or part of a value. `mask: url(v-bind(logoUrl))` would expand to `mask: url(/path/to/logo.png)`. This should work. But mask with a PNG... the PNG would need alpha channel for the mask to work. If logo.png has transparency, the mask would show the shape. But this is a logo — wouldn't you just want to DISPLAY the PNG as an `<img>`? Using mask means the logo takes the color of `currentColor` or `background`. The plan says \"color via currentColor\" for VisualBackground, and Logo.vue has a `color` prop. So the logo is meant to be a single-color mask that inherits color. This is a design choice. If logo.png is a full-color image, masking it would lose the colors. But if it's a monochrome silhouette, masking works. The source is `logo.png` — I can't see it but the plan assumes it works as a mask. This is acceptable for a plan.\n\nLet me finalize. I'll flag:\n1. [medium] npx tsx not in deps → use `bun run` or add tsx devDep\n2. [medium] theme-color #0e0f12 stale in nuxt.config.ts → update to match new --bg or switch to var() \n3. [medium] svg-import-strategy @VisualBackground.vue → specify static import map or import.meta.glob; dynamic string interpolation won't resolve in Vite\n4. [medium] tokens.scss diverges from tailwind.config.ts palette → acknowledge divergence or keep same hex for shared tokens\n\nActually, let me reconsider #4. The PROJECT_RULES say raw hex only in tokens.scss + fallback file. tailwind.config.ts has raw hex but it's pre-existing and out of write scope. The plan INTRODUCES new hex in tokens.scss that differ from tailwind. This isn't a rule violation (tokens.scss is allowed to have hex). The issue is the divergence creating inconsistency. But since the app doesn't use Tailwind color utilities, the practical impact is near zero. I think this is borderline. I'll keep it as medium but low priority.\n\nActually, I realize I should focus on the most impactful issues. Let me reconsider:\n\nThe npx tsx issue is real and verifiable (tsx not in package.json). The theme-color issue is real (stale hex in an allowed-path file). The SVG import strategy is a real design gap. The tailwind divergence is more theoretical.\n\nLet me also check: does the plan address how `--reduced-motion` gets set as a CSS var? The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns `--reduced-motion`. But who calls visualStateToCssVars and sets these vars on :root? The plan says VisualBackground reads `--reduced-motion` via getComputedStyle. But for --reduced-motion to be available, someone must set it on :root. The plan doesn't mention a step that applies visualStateToCssVars output to the DOM. The fallback would be set in tokens.scss? The plan's tokens.scss doesn't list --reduced-motion. visual-state.ts returns it, but who applies it? This is a gap — the plan doesn't specify how visualStateToCssVars output gets applied to :root. For P09, maybe the fallback is hardcoded in tokens.scss? But tokens.scss doesn't list --reduced-motion in its token list. So --reduced-motion would be undefined when VisualBackground reads it via getComputedStyle. This is a medium issue.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"visualStateToCssVars(state, settings?) → Record<string,string>. Returns --accent, --bg-variant, ..., --reduced-motion.\" And VisualBackground \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via getComputedStyle in onMounted\". But the plan doesn't say WHO calls visualStateToCssVars and applies the result to the DOM. For P09, there's no backend wiring (NOT doing: backend). So how does --reduced-motion get set? If nobody calls visualStateToCssVars, then --reduced-motion is never set, and VisualBackground's getComputedStyle would return empty. The fallback should be in tokens.scss. But tokens.scss doesn't list --reduced-motion. This is a real gap. Medium.\n\nActually, the plan says tokens.scss includes \"non-color: ... --motion-fast/med, --safe-*\". It doesn't mention --reduced-motion as a default in tokens.scss. And visualStateToCssVars returns --reduced-motion. But since no one applies visualStateToCssVars in P09, the default should be in tokens.scss. The plan should add `--reduced-motion: 0` (or similar) as a default in tokens.scss. This is a medium issue.\n\nLet me also check: VisualBackground reads `--reduced-motion` via getComputedStyle in onMounted. But the plan also says \"use @media (prefers-reduced-motion)\". So VisualBackground has TWO mechanisms: the OS-level media query AND the CSS var. This is redundant but OK. The issue is that the CSS var --reduced-motion has no default if nobody sets it.\n\nOK let me also reconsider the `--accent` default. tokens.scss says \"--accent default #7dd3fc (runtime, from catalog, non-lilac)\". So tokens.scss sets `--accent: #7dd3fc` as a default. Then visualStateToCssVars can override it. OK. But --reduced-motion has no default in tokens.scss. The plan should add it.\n\nLet me compile the final issues:\n\n1. [medium] no-verify @shared/visual/scatter.ts self-check → tsx is not in package.json devDependencies; use `bun run` or add tsx as devDep before claiming the command works\n2. [medium] stale-theme-color @apps/mobile/nuxt.config.ts:31 → update theme-color meta from #0e0f12 to match new --bg #0D0F17, or note it stays stale intentionally\n3. [medium] missing-css-var-default @tokens.scss → add --reduced-motion default (e.g. 0) in tokens.scss; VisualBackground reads it via getComputedStyle but nothing sets it in P09\n4. [medium] svg-import-strategy @VisualBackground.vue → specify static import map or import.meta.glob; dynamic string interpolation in import paths won't resolve in Vite\n\nActually, #4 — let me reconsider. The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". This sounds like it's describing static imports for each SVG (import each = one import per file). With 6 SVGs, you'd have 6 static imports. Then you'd need a name→url map. The plan says assets.ts has MAGIC_SVG_FILES=['magic-spark',...6]. VisualBackground could create a map from these names to imported URLs. The plan doesn't explicitly say \"create a name→url lookup map\" but it's implied by \"import each svg url\" + scatterLayout returning asset names. I think this is more of a design detail that a competent implementer would handle. But the plan should be explicit. I'll keep it as medium.\n\nLet me also reconsider whether the tailwind divergence is worth flagging. The plan changes --accent from lilac (#7c5cff) to sky (#7dd3fc). tailwind.config.ts still has `accent: \"#7c5cff\"`. If any future component uses `class=\"text-accent\"` (Tailwind), it would show lilac while `var(--accent)` shows sky. This is a real inconsistency. But the app doesn't currently use Tailwind accent classes. I'll mention it as a medium issue since the plan creates a palette divergence with a file it can't touch, and doesn't acknowledge it.\n\nActually, I already have 4 solid medium issues. Let me check if I have room for more or if 4 is enough. Max 8. Let me add the tailwind one as #5.\n\n5. [medium] palette-divergence @tailwind.config.ts → plan changes canonical hex in tokens.scss but tailwind.config.ts (out of scope) keeps old hex; acknowledge divergence or keep shared token hex identical\n\nHmm, actually, I want to be careful not to over-flag. Let me re-assess:\n\n- #1 (npx tsx): solid, verifiable, real\n- #2 (theme-color): solid, verifiable, real\n- #3 (--reduced-motion default): solid, real design gap\n- #4 (SVG import): medium, design detail gap\n- #5 (palette divergence): borderline, theoretical\n\nI'll include all 5 but make #5 concise. Actually, let me drop #5 since it's borderline and the app doesn't use Tailwind color classes. The practical impact is near zero. I'll keep the top 4.\n\nWait, actually there's one more thing. The plan says \"main.scss — replace :root{...} block with @use './tokens.scss'\". But `@use` in SCSS must come before any other rules. The current main.scss has `:root{...}` at the top, followed by `*`, `html,body,#__nuxt`, `body`, etc. Replacing `:root{...}` with `@use './tokens.scss'` puts the @use at the top, which is correct. But `@use` loads tokens.scss as a module. If tokens.scss contains `:root { ... }` as plain CSS (not in a mixin/function), the `@use` will emit that CSS in the output. This should work. But there's a subtlety: `@use` namespaces members. For plain CSS rules like `:root {}`, they're emitted as-is. So this is fine.\n\nBut actually, the plan says tokens.scss is ~115 LOC and contains ALL the tokens. If tokens.scss has `:root { --bg: #0D0F17; ... }`, then `@use './tokens.scss'` in main.scss would emit that `:root` block. Good. But the plan also says tokens.scss has \"Semantic aliases via var()\" and \"Legacy P10-compat utility tokens via var()\" — all inside `:root`. So the entire `:root` block comes from tokens.scss. main.scss just does `@use` + body/focus/etc. This is clean. OK, no issue here.\n\nOne more: the plan says tokens.scss has \"Variant tints (raw hex only here): --bg-dark-ember/--bg-deep-forest/--bg-midnight, --card-graphite/--card-pine/--card-plum, --profile-quiet-grid/--profile-night-lines/--profile-calm-shapes\". These are the variant backgrounds for the 3 background_variant, 3 card_variant, and 3 profile_background options. visualStateToCssVars returns --bg-variant, --card-variant, --profile-bg. These would reference the variant tint tokens. E.g., `--bg-variant: var(--bg-dark-ember)` when background_variant is \"dark-ember\". This means tokens.scss defines all 9 variant tints as raw hex, and visualStateToCssVars picks the right one. But how does visualStateToCssVars set --bg-variant? It returns a Record<string,string> like `{ '--bg-variant': 'var(--bg-dark-ember)' }`. Then whoever applies these vars to :root would override --bg-variant. But in P09, nobody applies them. So the default --bg-variant would need to be in tokens.scss too. The plan doesn't list --bg-variant as a default in tokens.scss (only the individual tints). So there's no default --bg-variant. Hmm, but if nobody applies visualStateToCssVars in P09, then --bg-variant is just undefined, and components that use it would fall back to... nothing. Is --bg-variant used by any existing component? No — it's a new token. So for P09, it's just defined but unused. The fallback would kick in when P11 wires the backend. OK, this is acceptable for P09 — these tokens are defined for future use.\n\nBut --reduced-motion IS used by VisualBackground in P09. So it needs a default. This confirms issue #3.\n\nLet me finalize with 4 issues.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the plan on VisualBackground more carefully: \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via v-bind-less approach: use @media (prefers-reduced-motion) + check --reduced-motion var with getComputedStyle in onMounted → set local reduced ref.\"\n\nSo VisualBackground checks BOTH @media (prefers-reduced-motion) AND the --reduced-motion CSS var. If --reduced-motion is not set (empty string from getComputedStyle), the component would treat it as not reduced. The @media query is the fallback. So even without --reduced-motion being set, the @media query would catch OS-level reduced motion. The --reduced-motion var is an additional check for app-level reduced motion (from Settings.reduced_motion). In P09, since nobody sets --reduced-motion, only the @media query works. This is actually OK for P09 — the @media query is the primary mechanism, and the CSS var is a bonus for when settings are wired. So maybe #3 isn't as critical. But the plan should still set a default --reduced-motion in tokens.scss for consistency. Hmm. I'll downgrade #3 to... actually, let me keep it. The plan says visualStateToCssVars returns --reduced-motion, and VisualBackground reads it. If tokens.scss doesn't define a default, getComputedStyle returns \"\" which is falsy. The component handles it (falls back to @media). So it works but the missing default is a minor gap. I'll keep it as medium since it's a real gap in the token definitions.\n\nActually no — if getComputedStyle returns \"\" for --reduced-motion, and the code checks `if (val === '1' || val === 'true')`, then empty string = not reduced. This is correct behavior. The missing default doesn't break anything. I think this is actually a low/nit. Let me drop it.\n\nHmm, but the plan does say VisualBackground \"reads --reduced-motion CSS var via getComputedStyle\" — if the var doesn't exist, this is a no-op. The @media query covers it. So it's fine. I'll drop #3.\n\nLet me reconsider my final list:\n1. [medium] npx tsx not in deps\n2. [medium] theme-color stale\n3. [medium] SVG import strategy vague\n\nThat's 3 solid medium issues. Let me see if there are any high issues.\n\nHigh issues: violations of PROJECT_RULES, references to non-existent files/symbols, commands that won't produce claimed results, plan-impl contradictions (no impl yet, so N/A), unhandled failure modes.\n\n- npx tsx not producing claimed result → this could be high if the acceptance gate depends on it. The acceptance gate says \"tsx self-checks pass