lan changes the bg color. It's an objective inconsistency. Medium.\n\nFinal answer: 3 medium issues.\n\nWait, actually let me reconsider whether the SVG import is really an issue with the plan. The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". The phrase \"import each\" suggests doing a static import for each SVG file. If you do:\n```ts\nimport magicSpark from '~/assets/brand/magic-spark.svg'\nimport magicCurl from '~/assets/brand/magic-curl.svg'\n// etc.\n```\nThen create a map:\n```ts\nconst svgUrls = { 'magic-spark': magicSpark, 'magic-curl': magicCurl, ... }\n```\nAnd scatterLayout returns asset names that index into this map. This works. The plan says \"import each svg url\" which implies static imports. So maybe the plan IS clear enough — \"import each\" = static import per file. The implementer would naturally create the map. I think this might not be a real issue. Let me drop it.\n\nHmm, but the plan uses the notation `~/assets/brand/<name>.svg` with angle brackets, which looks like a template/placeholder, not a literal path. This could be misinterpreted as dynamic import. But \"import each\" clarifies it's per-file static imports. I think this is borderline. I'll keep it as medium since the `<name>` notation is ambiguous and could lead to a non-working dynamic import.\n\nOK, final final list: 3 issues. Let me write it.\n\nActually, I realize I should also check: does the plan specify how VisualBackground gets the scatter items? It says \"renders scatterLayout(detail) items as positioned <span> mask SVGs\". So VisualBackground calls scatterLayout(props.decorativeDetail) to get ScatterItem[], then renders each as a positioned span with a mask SVG. Each ScatterItem has {x, y, rotation, scale, asset}. The `asset` field is a string name like 'magic-spark'. VisualBackground needs to map this to an imported SVG URL. The plan says \"import each svg url via ~/assets/brand/<name>.svg\". So the mapping is needed. This is a design detail. I'll keep t